Commentary.Commentary: The hosts are pursuing not a big score to get into the lead but do not underestimate the English bowlers. They can be destructive on any given day and the Proteas would need to bat extremely well on this wicket.
Now, the South African openers are out in the middle. Dean Elgar and Pieter Malan are two men for South Africa. James Anderson with the ball for the visitors first up. 3 slips in place.

South African bowlers were excellent on Day 1 and did not offer any easy runs for the visitors. They struck early but England did offer resistance with a few partnership but before they could turn into a bigger one, South Africa chipped away the wickets to keep their total to 269. All the bowlers took at least a wicket for the hosts.

Earlier on Day 1, England opted to bat first after winning the toss. Apart from Crawley, all the batters got starts but could not convert them into a big one as South Africa kept taking wickets at regular intervals. England looked at a decent position when they were 221/5 but a collapse saw them slump to 234/9. Pope hung on with Anderson for the final wicket and scored an unbeaten half ton.

17 legal deliveries is all South Africa needed to remove the final wicket and close the innings. No century for Pope then but he has played a very important hand to take the English total to 269. Rabada finishes off with a 3-fer here.

OUT! Caught at slip! Rabada has done the job for the Proteas and Anderson cannot manage to see off the over. A shortish ball outside off, Anderson looks to fend at it, away from his body off the back foot. An outside edge is induced and it goes straight to van der Dussen at first slip. ENGLAND ARE ALL OUT FOR 269.
Landed around off, Anderson keeps it out.
This time he is beaten but no edge on it so he won't mind. A good length ball around off, Anderson looks to defend but plays down the wrong line to get beaten.
Anderson does well with the first one he faces. A fuller ball on off, James taps it towards cover.

Oops! Misjudgement on the part of Pope. He thought he'd be able to steal the second but that wasn't on offer. A fuller ball on middle, Pope works it towards long on and takes off for the run. Only a single as the fielder there rushed to the ball quickly. So, 5 potential balls for Anderson to survive.

Over mid off! Just a single again and Pope keeps the strike again. A short of a length ball outside off, Pope looks to slam it over mid off but mistimes it. However, the timing is good enough to clear Philander at mid off. The batters can get a couple before Philander can get to the ball but only one is what they want.
WIDE! Another bumper which is over the head of Pope and this time the umpire calls it wide. This is around off, Pope lets it be.

Goes for the mighty pull to this one but does not make any connection. A back of a length ball on middle, Pope looks to pull but fails. Called one for the over as it was just around Pope's head height.
Beaten! First time this morning! Good length ball just outside off, Pope pokes at the ball to get beaten as it straightens a touch.
Fuller again, Pope pushes it towards sweeper cover. Singles are on offer for Pope but he is not interested. Boundaries are what he is looking for and singles only on the 5th or 6th ball, if possible.
Shortish around off, tapped towards cover by Pope this time.
Nortje starts with a good length ball around off, Pope comes forward and blocks it towards mid off.
Anrich Nortje to bowl from the other end. Just 1 slip in place.
Quick run! Pope will keep the strike. A back of a length ball on middle, Pope does well to tuck it towards square leg and takes a quick single.
Bouncer on middle and leg. Pope ducks under it with ease.
Full and on middle again, Pope whips it wide of long on and before the long on fielder can get to the ball, a couple of runs for Pope.
Yorker around off, Pope jams it out.
Fuller and outside off, it is pushed to covers by Pope.

Runs straightaway! A fuller ball outside off from Rabada, Anderson dabs it towards gully where the fielder cannot stop the ball cleanly. A single for Anderson on the very first ball. Now, Pope will look to farm the strike from hereon.

The South Africans walk out to the middle and they will be hoping that it is not for a long time as they have to take just one wicket. Out come the overnight batters too, Ollie Pope and James Anderson. Kagiso Rabada will start off the proceedings with James Anderson on strike. Here we go!

South Africa should've been coming out to bat now but Rabada overstepped late in the day and well, Pope and Anderson then added 28 unbeaten runs to take England towards a decent first innings total. 262 on the board with 1 wicket in hand. How many more can England add to this total? Can they get around the 300-run mark? Big mental advantage, you know.  The hosts will be eager to get rid of the final wicket to bundle out England before the total gets even bigger. We will soon find out how things pan out on Day 2. Welcome to our coverage for the same.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

Right! 9 wickets fall on Day 1 then. Should have been 10 but Rabada overstepped. What will Day 2 hold in store? Do England have enough? Mind you, they are not done yet. Can they get to 300? Can Pope play a blinder and reach his century? Can Anderson rekindle his 2009 Cardiff memories from the Ashes and hang around? Ufff... too many questions. Take a break. Sleep over those. Think over those. Or rather, do neither. Just ignore the questions and come back on Saturday, 4th January, 2020 at 10.30 am local (0830 GMT) for all the action from Day 2. ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

South Africa's bowling coach Charles Langeveldt need not be too unhappy either. He will be worried about that poor last 30 minutes but on the whole, it was a decent outing for his bowlers. Everyone bowled well but Anrich Nortje and Dwaine Pretorius were the most impressive. The question always asked is not what can your strike bowlers do. But what can your backup guys after the strike bowlers do. Nortje and Pretorius did not disappoint. They sustained the pressure built up by the opening bowlers and that resulted in the eventual fall of wickets.

It is very difficult to bat with a partner of lesser ability than yours and Pope learnt that here. But he kept his cool and just hung in there. He managed to farm the strike with James Anderson and has added 28 crucial runs so far, getting his half century also in the process. Who knows how vital they might turn out to be?

A day of starts for England. Apart from Zak Crawley, every dismissed batsman in the top 7 got in but then got out. They stuck in there, saw off difficult periods but just when it was time to reap benefits of that hard work, they threw it away. The period before the second new ball then decelerated their progress rapidly. Buttler fell in the 75th over and the visitors lost 4/13 in the span of 43 balls. But then, they were saved by the Pope. Well, jokes apart, not THE Pope, but Ollie Pope.

Exclude that last manic half an hour and it has been a wonderful day for South Africa. You lose the toss and have the opposition 9 down  for a shade over 250, of course you will be happy. But looking at the inconsistent bounce in the pitch, wonder if England would not be too unhappy?
Another bouncer, down the leg side again, ducked under again. OVER AND TIME, says Paul Reiffel. STUMPS ON DAY 1!
A bouncer, down the leg side, ducked under.
Short and outside off, cut straight to deep point.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Landed outside off, played straight to point.
Short and outside off, cut through point but does not take the single.
Around middle and leg again, worked towards square leg again. An eventful over, should have been the last of the day and the innings but KG... gone to junior KG.
Around middle and leg, tucked towards square leg.

CAUGHT OFF A NO BALL! This is really poor from Rabada. First, he does not bowl to the field and second, he has overstepped now. A short ball again, at the body, Pope comes down the track and looks to swat this out of the park. But he is cramped for room and gets a top edge. The ball swirls in the air towards fine leg where Vernon Philander comes running in, does really well to focus on the ball and takes a very good catch. The players are ready to head off the field but umpire Dharmasena wants to check for the overstepping. And yes, replays confirm that Rabada has overstepped. Now, the umpire wants to check whether the batsmen had crossed when the catch was being taken. Yup, the batsmen had crossed, as per the replays. So Anderson will face the remaining two balls of this over. Interestingly, Mike Atherton on air informs us that two balls before Rabada had overstepped but it was not called!
CAUGHT! But has Rabada overstepped? Dear me, he has! Schoolboy stuff. The umpires are checking whether the batsmen crossed when the catch was being taken. Yup. Jimmy on strike now.
A fly slip comes in place again.

FOUR! There he goes again! What is more interesting is, Faf's reaction. He throws his arms in the air, as if to ask his bowler - 'Why did you bowl that?' Because just before this ball, the captain removed that man from fly slip and got him to second slip. So short ball was definitely not the plan. But Rabada, like a bad student, does not pay heed to his captain's instructions. Bowls it short and Pope ramps it over the keeper, to the third man fence.
Landed outside off, dabbed to third man. No single taken.
Just an FYI - around 10 minutes left for Stumps. Even if England get bowled out now, South Africa WILL NOT bat tonight.
Full and around off, watchfully defended.
That stays low. On a length outside off, Pope stays inside the line and pushes hard but the ball shoots low and beats the inside edge. Lands short of the keeper.
OOOHH... ALMOST! Full and around middle, Anderson looks to flick and it nearly goes straight to short leg! Lands just short.

HALF CENTURY FOR OLLIE POPE! Just his second in Tests but it has been his best innings so far in this format. Because it has been under immense pressure. A short ball outside off, Pope pulls it uppishly, through the massive vacant areas at mid-wicket. Dean Elgar gives it a good chase from deep square leg and puts in a slide to stop the ball. Three runs taken.
The field comes up now. So do the two batsmen, towards each other, for a brief chat. Mind games. Everyone is ready but at the last moment, Nortje goes towards mid off for some strategy discussion.
A bouncer on off, Ollie ducks and sways at the same time, in time.
Outside off, flashed through point. No single taken again.
A length ball outside off, coming in with the angle, Pope looks to tap and run but then changes his mind.
Short and outside off, cut behind point to get his half century. To NOT get his half century. Team first. First ball. Denies the single.
Anrich Nortje returns. 15-1-51-2 so far.
A sharp bouncer, outside off, Jimmy looks to fend but the ball keeps on rising and coming in. Beats his poke. Anderson has seen off an entire over.

Jimmy gets some runs! Well, the crowd has actually stood up as one to applaud. Landed outside off, on a length, JA plays this away from his body and gets it through cover-point. Two runs taken. The stand is worth 20 now, from 23 balls.
Good bowling. Targets the yorker, bowls it very full and straight. But Anderson keeps it out. The crowd cheers again.
Ooohhh... nervy. A length ball outside off, JA looks to play the upper cut, but then misses due to the steep bounce.
Outside off, another solid defense, to the off side.
Cheer from the crowd! Jimmy keeps one out from this over. A length ball around off, Anderson gets right behind this one and blocks.
FOUR! Much better shot this time. A length ball, on middle, Pope comes down the track and lofts it over mid on. One bounce and into the ropes. 250 UP FOR ENGLAND!
FOUR! Just over! Full and outside off, Pope walks into the shot and lofts it over mid off. Kagiso Rabada moving to his left leaps but the ball goes over him.
Down the leg side, worked straight to mid-wicket.
Defended off the back foot by the batsman.
Full and outside off, pushed straight to cover.
Close call. Full and outside off, Anderson pushes at it away from his body and gets a thick inside edge. It just misses the leg stump, en route fine leg. A single taken.

MISCALCULATION! Pope is on his haunches, smiling. That was not how he calculated. A short ball outside off, Pope looks to clobber that back past the bowler. But he mistimes it. Rabada stretches out his left hand but it just eludes him and beats mid off. Now, Anrich Nortje is running after it from mid off and Pope has to think about a single or three. He chooses the latter. Takes two and Jimmy is ready for the third, turning blind. But Pope rightly sends him back, as he is not sure whether he will make it in time to the bowler's end. Good decision in the end as the throw was pretty sharp. But why did he not just settle for a single?
Everybody is being brought up now.
Outside off, once again, Ollie looks to play the ramp but misses.

FOUR! A cheeky shot! A shot which plenty of youngsters love to play these days. That is not to suggest that I am old, by any means. A short ball, around off, coming in with the angle, following the batsman. Pope initially looks to duck but at the last moment, plays the upper cut, right back over the keeper's head! One bounce and into the fence.
Full and outside off, wide again, OP crashes this through the covers but this time, straight to Maharaj at sweeper.
A bit wider outside off, Ollie crashes this in front of sweeper, just past cover. Keshav Maharaj has a bit of an area to sweep to his right. So by the time he covers that portion, two runs are taken.
A short ball wide outside off, Pope slashes hard but misses.
Both balls survived. Full and wide outside off, either a bad ball or bowled with a plan to tempt Jimmy into the drive. But it is left alone.
1 survived. The crowd cheers. Plenty of English supporters today. Full and outside off, Anderson shoulders arms.
Full and wide outside off, OP drives it through point for a single. 2 balls left for Jimmy to survive.
Full and straight, pushed towards mid on.
Beauty. On a length outside off, Ollie looks to push but the ball moves away late off the seam and beats the outside edge.
Full and wide outside off, Pope slashes hard to sweeper cover. Does not take the single.
James Anderson is the last man in.

OUT! BOWLED! Broady, Broady, what happened there? Poor lad. 73 matches before he got on the helmet by a vicious Varun Aaron bouncer. Has never been the same since. He is always expecting a bouncer first up. Bowlers all over the world are terrorizing him now, threatening bouncers, but then slipping in fuller ones. Rabada does exactly that. Broad is deep in his crease, expecting a short one. But he gets a fuller one. Now, here is the height of all misfortunes. Stuart does get his bat down. But while coming down, the willow gets stuck behind his front pad! The ball meets no obstruction and clatters the stumps.
Gets the single he wanted. A length ball outside off, OP steers it behind point for a run.
A length ball outside off, Ollie looks to defend but the ball moves away and takes the outside edge. Goes towards point.
A bouncer on middle, Pope ducks.
Around off, defended towards cover.
No looseners. A perfect start. Full and just outside off, watchfully defended.
Kagiso Rabada to share the second new ball with the big Vern. 14-3-47-1 so far.
Goes for the booming inswinger but ends up spraying it on the pads. Pope flicks it towards square leg in the deep for a single.
And again. This is slightly wider outside off, OP launches a massive cover drive, only to miss again.
Aha... Movement through the air for Vernon. Outside off, on a length, Ollie flashes a drive but misses.
Around off, tucked through mid-wicket for a single.
A length ball, around middle, swinging in, Broad misses his flick and is hit on the pads.
Stuart Broad walks in at number 10, replacing Bess.

OUT! Caught behind! Philander strikes with the first ball in his first spell with the second new ball. That is the end of Bess. England in a mess. A typical Vernon dismissal. Ask questions. Put the ball in that avenue of apprehension. Sow the seed of doubt in the batsman's mind. Should I play? Should I leave? Will the ball move away? Will the ball come in? What if I lose my stumps like Curran did? Poor Bess cannot be blamed entirely. He sees that pitch around the 4th stump outside off and is caught in two minds as to which way will the ball move. He looks to play this straight, down the ground but to his dismay, the ball pitches and then straightens. Enough to take the outside edge. Simple catch for Quinton de Kock. 3/10 in 32 balls!
GoaRocks - 'Hurray! The second new ball taken? Now, all out! Yippee!'
Interesting. THE SECOND NEW BALL HAS BEEN TAKEN. One might have thought Faf might delay it, due to this late burst of wickets. VERNON PHILANDER to make the first use of it. 13-3-34-1 so far.
The batsman defends it from within the crease.
Floated outside off, driven straight to cover.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Full and on middle, Pope comes down the track and looks to flick but hits it in the air. But there is no short leg or short mid-wicket present.
Outside off, punched off the back foot.
Short and outside off, cut straight to point.
Dominic Bess walks in at number 9, replacing Curran.

OUT! BOWLED! Now, Sir Geoffrey, sir Geoffrey, where are you? Ian Chappell, where art thou? Both of you, if present at the ground, or in the commentary box, would have said, 'Kid, you have a bat in hand. Just make use of that. You are not here to leave balls.' Terrible misjudgement from Sam. Not that a misjudgement is ever sweet. But that is a saying, so went with the flow. A length ball outside off, Curran shoulders arms. But the cherry comes back in with the angle and to his horror, shatters the stumps behind.

FOUR! Nicely done. Though, Pretorius will not mind it too much. Not a bad ball, by no means a half volley outside off. Curran has actually come forward and driven a ball which is short of full, on the up. There is a short extra cover and a mid off close to him, in place. But Sam has thread that gap to precision.
Around off, pushed towards mid on.
Full and outside off, driven straight to mid off.
On a length, outside off, coming in with the angle, pushed back to the bowler again.
A length ball outside off, coming in, watchfully defended.
Full again, OP reaches out and blocks.
Short and outside off, Ollie rocks back to cut but finds point.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Full and outside off, Pope lunges to defend.
Oohhh... Curran lunges to defend but the ball spins in, probably off the rough. Don't see much though. It bounces, takes the inside edge but there is no short leg. A run taken towards square leg.
Tossed up outside off, driven towards long off for a single.

INSIDE EDGE, MISSES THE STUMPS, FOUR! Things are happening here. A length ball outside off, Curran pushes at it away from his body. The ball though, comes in and cramps him for room. The inside edge is eked out and it goes behind, but JUST over the stumps, to the fine leg fence!
This time the cover drive is timed perfectly but straight to cover.
Cover drive to mid on. No, I am not done for the day. Yet. Full and outside off, Sam looks to drive but the ball swings back in and goes off the inner half of the bat towards mid on.
Around off, this is defended stoutly.

That was a ripper. On a length outside off, coming back in a long way, Curran looks to work it to the leg side but the ball shapes back in, beats the inside edge, hits the thigh and goes towards gully.
Around off, solidly defended.
Comes down the track now and defends.
Outside off, pushed straight to cover.
Full and wide outside off, plenty of flight, Pope reaches out and drives it straight to cover.
Comes down the track this time and drives but finds the bowler.
On middle, worked straight to short leg.
Full and around off, watchfully blocked out.
Into the all-rounders now. Sam Curran is the first of them.

OUT! Caught behind! Oh my. Did we say Buttler is at his best when he is busy at the crease? He is now gone. Just what South Africa would have wanted before the second new ball is taken. The walk on the move has removed Buttler. Pretorius maintains his line and length outside off and Jos, by habit, looks to push. But the ball nibbles away off the seam and squares him up. There is a noise as the ball goes past the bat and de Kock and Pretorius go up. The finger from the man who matters the most goes up as well. Joseph does not bother waiting. Ultra Edge shows a thin spike. Another start wasted.
Outside off, played through point for a couple.
Around off, on a length, watchfully blocked out.
FOUR! SWEET! Full and outside off, Buttler comes forward and drives this through the covers!
What happened there? Pretorius comes running in but aborts his runup midway.
Around off, watchfully defended.

Oh dear...rash, very rash. But this is also a sign that he is looking to be positive. He adopted this technique of walking down the track in the Test matches against India and it worked for him. He is at his best when he is busy. But this time, he walks into the shot, pushes at the ball but misses due to the late movement.
Around off, well defended.
Punched off the back foot by the batsman.
Full and around off, Pope comes down the track and blocks it.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Full on middle, Buttler comes down the track and pushes it to long on for a single.
On middle, punched off the back foot.

Drinks! An hour of play which has belonged to both sides. Stokes and Pope started well before Stokes threw it away with a poor shot. Buttler has come in and is looking edgy out there. Pope, though has looked comfortable and England need to put up a good partnership. South Africa will not be too disappointed but they would have been a little happier if they prized out a few more wickets.
Full delivery on off, Ollie pushes it to cover.

EDGY FOUR! Luck is favouring Ollie Pope out at Newlands. Full delivery on middle, Pope looks to push it but gets a thick outside edge which goes between the second slip and gully fielder. It flies into the fence.
Good length ball on middle and leg, Pope works it to square leg.
On off, Pope drives it beautifully but finds the cover fielder.
Full outside off, left alone.
Well fielded! Full delivery outside off, Pope drives it beautifully through covers and picks up a couple. Malan puts in a terrific run and makes a good sliding stop.
Dwaine Pretorius is back on.
On middle, defended back to the bowler.
Flatter delivery on off, Buttler cuts but finds the point fielder.
Floated ball on off, Buttler lunges and blocks it to point.
Short ball on off, Jos pushes it to cover.
Flatter delivery outside off, Buttler pushes it to point.
There is a slight halt in play as the ball was lost after that six from Buttler.
SIX! Gets that one does Buttler. Floated ball on middle, Buttler dances down and heaves it over the long on region for a biggie.
On a length outside off, Pope leaves it alone.

Just short! Full delivery on off, Pope looks to drive it but gets a thick outside edge which goes towards second slip. The fielder comes forward in an attempt to catch but it falls short. Luck favouring Pope out there.
Short of a length on middle, Pope has no problems in ducking under it.
BOUNCER! It is bowled around middle and leg, Pope ducks under it.
Good length on middle, Ollie solidly blocks it.
Full on middle, Pope defends it out.
Played to the mid-wicket region by the batsman. One run added to the total.

Was that a drop catch? From the reactions it certainly does look like it. Floated on off, Buttler drives it uppishly to silly mid off. It goes in between the legs of  him and through mid off. A single taken. The replays show that it might have burst through his hands but even if it was, it was a tough one.
Flatter delivery on middle, Jos defends it out.
On off, defended off the back foot to cover.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.

FOUR! Clever shot but risky as well. Floated ball on middle, Buttler plays the paddle sweep to fine leg. Vernon Philander hares after it and slides to make a stop. The umpires go in to check whether it is a four. The replays confirm that Philander has touched the ropes while trying to push the ball away.
Good length ball on off, Buttler taps it to point and calls Pope for a quick single. The fielder has a shy at the keeper's end but misses. Pope was in though.
Full delivery on off, Jos defends it out.
Short of a length around off, Buttler looks to pull at first but then gets his bat out in time. Lets it go to the keeper.

FOUR! But Buttler was lucky there. If he had missed, it would have been crashing into the stumps. Nortje bowls a full delivery on middle, Buttler moves to the off side and manages to get bat on it and flicks it to the fine leg region for a boundary.
Full on off, Jos defends it out to Nortje.
There we go again. He is unafraid, the hadeda. Halts play for a bit again, hopping across on the outfield.

FOUR! That will give Buttler some confidence. He has been out of touch for some while now. On a length outside off, Buttler camps back and punches it off the back foot through covers for a boundary. Two fielders chase after it but the ball wins the race.
Loopy delivery around off, Ollie takes a stride forward and pushes it to point.
Tossed up ball on middle, Pope comes down the pitch and flicks it to mid-wicket.
Fuller one outside off, Pope drives it to cover for nothing.
Flat one on middle and leg, Ollie pushes it back to the bowler.
On off, Pope lunges forward and defends it out.
Loopy delivery on middle, Buttler works it wide of mid on and takes a single.
Around off, solidly defended back to the bowler.
A bouncer now, Pope ducks.
Streaky start. Full and around off, Buttler looks to work it to the leg side but the ball moves away slightly and goes off the leading edge through the covers. A single taken.
Jos Buttler walks in now. Under a lot of criticism. Needs runs. Needs big runs. For starters, he should be there when the first ball is bowled tomorrow morning. With the bat in hand.

OUT! CAUGHT AT COVER! Gosh, gosh, gosh. Both sides would be thinking about that word. Just when England seemed well on top, right from nowhere, a wicket has fallen. And it is the man who scored a double century the first time he batted here in Tests. Ben Stokes looks at the ground crestfallen. He takes half a minute or so and then trudges off. This is a big boost for the Proteas. Full and outside off, Stokes looks to drive but his bottom hand comes off the bat. As a result, he is not in control of the shot and the ball flies off the face of the bat, straight to Dean Elgar at short cover. This did not hit a divot. This did not deviate off the seam. This did not swing in the air. Like many unexplained things in the universe, this just happened. Perhaps, when you are facing a bloke bowling close to 90 miles an hour, you sometimes do not have control of your shots. This was one of those times. This is what pace brings to Test cricket.
Full and around off, Stokes walks forward and pushes it back to the bowler.
Full and around off, pushed towards mid on for a very quick single.
On middle, pushed towards mid on.
Full and around off, watchfully defended.

NOT OUT! Umpire's call it is on hitting the stumps. It is not a bad decision to review in the end as it looked very close. Maharaj floats this one up on middle and leg, Pope looks to defend it but gets hit flush on the pads. Maharaj appeals but the umpire shakes his head. Maharaj is confident and convinces Faf to go for the review. The Ultra Edge rolls in and it shows that there was no bat on it. The Ball Tracker is up now and it is umpire's call on hitting the leg stump. The Proteas do not lose a review.

Close, close, pretty close! No, says umpire Kumara Dharmasena. Inside edge? Missing leg? Faf du Plessis signals for the LBW review. Seems to be going down leg to the naked eye. UMPIRE'S CALL. It is clipping the leg stump on height!
On middle, Stokes flicks it to the leg side for a single.
On middle, Ben defends it back to Maharaj.
FOUR! A poor ball and Stokes makes full use of it. Not a length to bowl to a batsman like Stokes. Short of a length on middle, Stokes camps back and pulls it to deep square leg for a boundary.
On middle, Stokes works it to deep square leg and takes a single.

FOUR! Smashed! Back of a length ball outside off, Stokes stands tall and punches it through the covers for a boundary. 50-run stand is up between the two. England needed it after losing two quick wickets.
Where has that come from? Back of a length ball around off which bounces a little more than what Stokes expected. He looks to defend but gets hit on the gloves. Very well bowled from Nortje.
On a length on off, Stokes defends it out.

SAFE! Almost did the trick! Short of a length on middle, Pope is late on his pull but gets a top edge but luckily for him it just goes over Vernon Philander at mid off. Before he can clean it up the batters take a single.
Nortje starts with a fuller one outside off, Ollie does not fiddle with it and leaves it alone.
Anrich Nortje is back on. 11-0-34-1, his figures so far.
SIX! Finally we see a maximum in this game! Maharaj tosses this one up on middle, Stokes puts on his dancing shoes and hammers it over the long on region for half a dozen.
Full on middle, Ben pushes it to mid on.
On middle, Stokes tucks it to mid-wicket.
Flat on middle and leg, Ben blocks it,
Flatter one on middle, Ben defends it out.
Short of a length on middle, Stokes pulls it to square leg. The fielder fails to collect it cleanly but no run.
On off, driven to mid off.
Vernon bowls another one which is full outside off, Pope solidly pushes it to point.
Good length on off, Pope taps it to point.
On off, Pope lunges forward and blocks it to cover.
Fuller one outside off, Ollie lets the ball go to the keeper.
Fuller one on middle, Pope defends it solidly off the front foot.
On middle and leg, worked to square leg where the fielder makes a good sliding stop.
Defended off the back foot by the batsman.
Loopy delivery on middle, Ben dances down and pushes it to mid on.
On middle, Stokes comes down the track and defends it back to the bowler.
Another flat one with some spin, Stokes works it to square leg.
Flatter one on middle, Stokes works it to the leg side.
Back of a length in the channel, Pope punches it to point off the back foot.
Good length on off, Ollie solidly defends it out.
FOUR! Errs in line does Philander and Pope does not miss out. Full delivery on the pads, Pope flicks it beautifully through the mid-wicket region for a boundary.
On a length on middle and leg, Stokes works it to deep square leg and picks up another run.

EDGY FOUR! Ooohhh... almost another wicket. Very rare from Stokes. He is a positive player, so he either goes hard at the balls or lets them go. Very rarely do we see him so indecisive about shot-making. This was one of those moments. A length ball outside off, Ben is in two minds, whether to play at that or let it go. In the end, he does try that run-down-to-third-man shot but is late and gets a thick outside edge. Luckily for him, it goes between second slip and gully and the ball races to the third man fence. Nasser Hussain on air calls it a 'One-Day shot'. We have seen Joe Root play that shot so often in every format and even today, he was cross with himself for getting out. The reason - you can leave balls pitched outside off. Rabada will be frustrated a touch that did not go to hand but he will also be happy that he is causing some doubts in Stokesy's mind.

Shoo away, hadeda! No, we are not joking. A hadeda has actually brought the game to a bit of a halt here. Anrich Nortje was charging in to bowl but he was stopped by Ben Stokes as he saw the bird casually pecking the grass at mid on, looking for food. Nortje goes back, tries to shoo the bird away but in a more of 'mind-your-own-business' style, it continues to go about its stuff and ignores Nortje. Eventually, Stokes, after realizing that he can watch the details better in a Discovery Channel better, decides to get on with it. We were actually struggling to find the name of that bird. So after a bit of a research, got the name. 'The hadeda ibis (Bostrychia hagedash), also called hadada, is an ibis native to Sub-Saharan Africa. It is named for its loud three to four note calls uttered in flight especially in the mornings and evenings when they fly out or return to their roost trees. Although not as dependent on water as some ibises, they are found near wetlands and often live in close proximity to humans, foraging in cultivated land and gardens. Bless you, researchers...

Now, post Lunch, Denly and Root will look to build another good stand and take England towards a good total. The hosts, on the other hand, will be eager to see the back of a few players in the coming session. Stay with us to find out.

The Proteas were brilliant with the ball, especially Philander who bowled on consistent lines and lengths. He got the reward as well as he removed Crawley in the 3rd over. After that, he along with Rabada did find a couple of outside edges but they went to the vacant region. Rabada broke the good-looking stand to end the session on an even note. Nortje and Pretorius were good too but they did not threaten much.

A shared session then. England were moving along nicely after the early blow, courtesy, a nice and compact 50-run stand between Sibley and Denly. After opting to bat first, England lost Crawley early but Sibley and Denly saw off the initial threat from Philander and Rabada after that. Once they got themselves settled, the duo batted well. It looked like both of them will see off the session but Sibley found himself poking at the ball he should've left alone and ended up losing his wicket. Denly and Root saw off the tricky phase to finish the session on 67/2.

OHH! Looped up ball on middle, Sibley comes down the track and looks to push it to the leg side but gets a thick outside edge. It rolls towards point.
Floated on middle and leg, Sibley works it to mid-wicket.
On off, Denly drives it to long off and picks up a single.
Starts with a flighted ball on off, Denly pushes it to cover.
Double change! Time for spin now as Keshav Maharaj has been introduced early into the attack. A slip and a short leg in place for him.
On a length outside off, Sibley lets the ball go to the keeper.
Fullish delivery on off, Sibley takes a stride forward and drives it through covers. The fielders from mid off and cover hare after it. The former slides and cleans it up. Two taken.
Length ball outside off, Sibley leaves it alone.
Full one on off, Sibley moves to the off side and defends it to mid on.
On middle, Dominic plays it back to the bowler.
Nortje starts with a fullish delivery on off, Sibley blocks it to point.
Change in bowling for the first time as Anrich Nortje comes into the attack.
Outside off, left alone by Denly.
On the pads, Sibley flicks it to deep square leg and picks up a single.
Good length delivery outside off, Sibley lets the ball go to the keeper.
BOUNCER! It is bowled around middle and off, Dominic does well to evade it.
Back of a length ball outside off, Sibley sways away from it.
Fullish outside off, Sibley shoulders arms to this one.
Short of a length on middle and leg, Joe ducks under it.
On a length on off, Joe defends it off the back foot.

FOUR! Hammered away! Short of a length on middle, Denly gets into position quickly and pulls it to the deep square leg region for a boundary. The fielder from fine leg gives it a chase  but fails to cut it off.
Fullish on off, Denly taps it to point.
On a length outside off shaping away, Joe looks to defend it but fails to get any bat on it. Brilliant bowling from Philander.
Good length delivery on middle but it bounces extra, Denly looks to defend it but it hits the handle of the bat and goes towards the leg side. No run.
BOUNCER! It is bowled around middle, Sibley ducks under it.
Fullish outside off, Sibley lets the ball through to the keeper.
Full on middle, Dominic works it to mid-wicket.
Good length on middle, Dominic blocks it to square leg.
Back of a length ball outside off, Sibley makes a leave to the keeper.
On a length on off, Denly looks to defend it but it goes off the inner half of the bat towards square leg. A single taken.
Good length ball outisde off, Sibley lets it go to the keeper.

BEATEN! Lovely delivery from Philander! Good length delivery around off nipping away from the batsman, Sibley looks to defend it but misses altogether. Philander seems interested for caught behind but the umpire shakes his head. Faf du Plessis is not interested for the review.
Fullish delivery outside off, Sibley does not fiddle with it and leaves it alone.
On middle, Dominic defends it off the back foot.
FOUR! Beautiful shot from Sibley. This will give him a lot of confidence. Fullish on off, Sibley leans forward and creams the drive through extra cover for a boundary.
Full delivery outside off, Sibley shoulders arms to this one.
In the channel outside off from Rabada, Denly makes a leave now.
Punched nicely! A fuller ball around off, Denly this time punches it through point. The ball is racing towards the fence but Malan from gully chases it down and keeps the batters to two.
Outside off, Denly this time covers his stumps and lets it be.
FOUR! Denly is off the mark in good fashion. A good length ball outside off, Denly reaches out and drives it through point to get his first boundary of the innings.
Another one which is on a good length around off, Denly blocks it out.
Good length around off, Denly pushes it towards cover by getting behind the line of the ball.
Outside off, it is left alone.

Now this one comes back in. Good length ball around off, it comes into Sibley sharply as he looks to defend it off the back foot. Sibley looks to defend but it seems like the ball took the inside edge and went onto the pads.

Follows it with another beauty. He can just keep landing the ball on the same spot and keep bothering the batters. That's what he is doing with Sibley. Pitches it slightly closer to the off pole on a good length and makes it move away from the defensive poke of Sibley.
Ripper! Absolute ripper! Good length ball around off, Sibley comes forward to defend but the ball moves away from his bat and goes behind. Lucky not to edge that one.
Shortish length ball around off, Sibley rides the bounce and taps it towards covers.
FOUR! Whipped away! A gift on the pads from Philander. Overpitched on the pads, Sibley flicks it brilliantly and it races to the deep mid-wicket fence.
Driven well but straight to the point fielder. So, Denly will remain on nought. A fuller ball outside off, Joe reaches out and creams the drive but straight to the fielder.
In the channel outside off, Denly makes another leave.
Landed around off, Denly comes forward and pushes it to mid off.
Outside off, it is left alone.
Fuller ball on off, Denly keeps it out.
Shortish length ball outside off, Denly has no problems in shouldering his arms.
Good leave! A good length ball that lands outside off, it comes back in nicely but Sibley has his timbers covered as he lets it go to the keeper.
Just ahead of a good length area, Sibley comes forward to defend but the ball takes the thick outside edge and goes to second slip but on the bounce.
Fullish outside off, left alone by Sibley.
On off, Sibley plays it with soft hands and guides it to gully. The fielder there slides and makes the stop.
On a length on off, Dominic stands tall and defends it to point.
Good length ball on middle, Sibley defends it off the back foot to the leg side.
Just short! Slightly fuller and outside off, Denly pokes at the ball with hard hands. The ball takes the outer half of the bat and goes to the gully fielder on the bounce.
Fullish and outside off again, Denly lets it be.
Good length ball around middle, tucked towards mid-wicket for a single.
Outside off, it is left alone.
EDGY FOUR! Length ball around off, Sibley looks to work it on the leg side but the ball takes the thickish outside edge and goes between third slip and gully. It races to the third man fence.
Slightly fuller around off, asking the batter to drive but Sibley is not lured into the shot as he makes a leave.
Joe Denly is the new man in.

OUT! Caught Behind! Brilliant from de Kock behind the wicket. Superb from Philander too. Continues bowling on the fourth stump channel on a good length. It swings away a bit. Crawley looks to defend off the front foot but the ball takes the outside edge and goes behind. De Kock dives to his right nicely and pouches it in his mitts. Top start for the Proteas. Not so good for England and Crawley.
Slightly fuller and around off, Crawley takes a good stride forward and blocks it out nicely.
Good length ball around off again, blocked onto the pitch by Zak.
Landed fullish around off, Crawley keeps it out.
Beaten! Brilliant from Philander. Another ball around off on a good length. It once again moves away from the forward defensive poke of Crawley.
Outside off, it is left alone.
Fuller ball just outside off, late swing on it too. Sibley looks to dig it out but gets beaten.
FOUR! Off the mark nicely! Not a very good ball from Rabada as he bowls it full and too straight. Sibley easily flicks it to the deep mid-wicket fence. First boundary of the innings.
Fuller again, this time just outside off, Crawley leans into the shot and drives it through covers. Before Maharaj can get to the ball with a slide, the batters take three.
Fullish ball outside off, some late swing on it too. Crawley looks to reach out and drive but pulls his bat away at the last moment.
Outside off, it is left alone.

Rabada is on the money straightaway too! A good length ball around off from him. Unlike Philander, Rabada makes it come into the right-hander. Crawley looks to defend but the ball whizzes past the outside edge.
Kagiso Rabada will bowl from the other end. Three slips and a gully in place for him.
Landed around off on a length, it is defended. A tight over from Philander. Always on the money is the Big Vern and nothing different here either from him.
This time Philander strays on the pads of Crawley. He easily works it behind square leg for a single to get the scoreboard ticking.

Follows it with another ripper! Pitches this one around off on a good length. Crawley has to play at it. He comes forward and looks to defend but a hint of movement is enough to beat the outside edge.
Beauty! Brilliant line and length from Philander. He pitches this one around off and makes it move away just a hint. Crawley pokes to get beaten.
This time Vernon bowls it in the channel outside off, Crawley makes a leave.
Philander starts with a good length ball around off, Crawley comes forward and blocks it off the front foot.

The English openers, Dominic Sibley and Zak Crawley walk out to the middle. The Protea players are already on the field. Vernon Philander will start the proceedings for the hosts with the ball. Zak Crawley to face first up. Here we go...
Both teams are making their way out to the ground to stand in respect of their respective National Anthems. England is up first followed by South Africa.

Faf du Plessis, South Africa skipper, says that he would've batted first on this wicket too. Tells that in the first session of Day 1, there's always something on the wicket. Tells that they would try to get 3-4 wickets in the first session. On Pieter Malan's debut, du Plessis says that it's a great chance for him and it's always good to be playing in front of your home crowd. Says that they have just won one Test and not really a lot of things change for them. Adds that there are still three Tests in this series against a quality side.

Joe Root, England skipper, tells that the surface is looking good to bat. Thanks the supporters for coming all the way from England to support them. Mentions three changes in the side that are Zak Crawley coming in for Rory Burns, Ollie Pope coming in for Jonny Bairstow and Dominic Bess is in for Jofra Archer. Says that Zak is a fine player who had a great season with Kent and now he has a chance to show how good he is. Feels this game is a challenge for everyone. On Ollie's inclusion, Root mentions that Ollie showed great performance during his game against New Zealand.

SOUTH AFRICA (PLAYING XI) - Pieter Malan (DEBUT, IN PLACE OF AIDEN MARKRAM), Dean Elgar, Zubayr Hamza, Rassie van der Dussen, Faf du Plessis (C), Quinton de Kock (WK), Dwaine Pretorius, Vernon Philander, Keshav Maharaj, Kagiso Rabada, Anrich Nortje.

ENGLAND (PLAYING XI) - Zak Crawley (IN PLACE OF RORY BURNS), Dominic Sibley, Joe Denly, Joe Root (C), Ben Stokes, Ollie Pope (IN PLACE OF JONNY BAIRSTOW), Jos Buttler (WK), Sam Curran, Dominic Bess (IN PLACE OF JOFRA ARCHER), Stuart Broad, James Anderson.
Toss - Up goes the coin and it lands in favour of England. They choose to bat first.

Update - Just before the toss, England have been dealt another blow as Jofra Archer has been ruled out of this Test due to an elbow injury. He will have second scan to understand the extent of his injury. Looks like a long list of changes is coming from the English side.

After 5 consecutive losses, South Africa bagged a win. It was not an easy one as England posed challenges at different phases. However, all-round South African performance trumped them in the end with the Protea pacers utilizing the second new ball well to shot down the threat from the English batters in the 4th innings. Now, the caravan moves to Newlands, Cape Town, a ground which is a happy hunting one for the hosts. Pieter Malan is set to make his Test debut as he replaces the injured Aiden Markram. England, on the other hand, are still dealing with viral to multiple players. To their misery, one of their in-form batter, Rory Burns has been ruled out of the series as he got injured while playing football. Now, who will replace him? Or who will partner Sibley at the top? England will have a task cut out in deciding their playing XI. How will things pan out? It's gonna be an interesting game for sure. Will we get to see the Protea juggernaut moving ahead or will the Three Lions bounce back to get level in the 4-match series. Hello and a warm welcome to the 2nd Test. Stay with us for the Toss and playing XI updates.

The hosts, on the other hand, would be disappointed with their performance. Apart from Dean Elgar and Rassie van der Dussen, no one got going. They were 40 for 3 at one stage and then a comeback of sorts happened. A 117-run stand between Elgar And van der Dussen made everyone think that they were in control. However, once Elgar and Quinton de Kock threw away their wickets, the Proteas never recovered and conceded a valuable lead of 46 runs. The South African bowlers have a tough task ahead as they need to pick up wickets at regular intervals in order to get back in this game. Can they make a comeback or will the visitors run away with the match? Join us in a while to find out.

26 balls is all it took for the English bowlers to take the two remaining South African wickets. They have put in an incredible effort in the field as they go back to the pavilion with a lead of 46 runs. Anderson and Broad were terrific from the start. They reduced the hosts to 40/3 but then Rassie van der Dussen and Dean Elgar combined to form a terrific stand of 117 runs. In that period, 12 No Balls were not picked by the on-field umpire. However, when van der Dussen was dismissed but the on-field umpire then referred upstairs to check for a No Ball and Rassie survived. Stokes dropped a catch too. It looked like South Africa would make them pay. But once Elgar fell, it was a procession as they lost their last six wickets for just 32 runs. James Anderson picked up a 5-fer, his 28th in Test cricket, surpassing the record for an English player set by legend, Sir Ian Botham. However, it was Stuart Broad who was the pick of the bowlers as he kept on bowling perfect lines and lengths throughout Day 2.

OUT! CAUGHT! 5-fer for James Anderson, his 28th in Test cricket! Brilliant from Stokes as well as he takes a stunning catch in the slip cordon. This is a terrific ball from James Anderson. A good length ball outside off, inducing the drive from Anrich Nortje. The batter obliges but he manages just an outside edge on it. The ball flies to the right of first slip and to the left of second slip. Stokes from second slip dives to his left and takes a superb catch to end the South African innings. Stokes takes his 5th catch of this innings and becomes the first outfield English player to do so. All smiles for the England players as they return to the pavilion.

Another bumper around off this time, Anrich ducks under it comfortably.
BOUNCER! It is bowled around middle and leg, Nortje looks to duck but falls down in the process.
On a length on off, Anrich pushes it to point.
Full delivery on middle, Vernon blocks it towards mid off and a single is taken.
On off, Nortje defends it well towards cover. That will be the end of another over and Nortje is doing well, for now at least.
Fullish on middle, Anrich pushes it down to mid on.
Fullish delivery outside off, Nortje lets the ball go through to the keeper.
Bouncer outside off, Nortje awkwardly sways away from it.

FOUR! Lovely batting from Nortje. The trail is now below 50. Full delivery on the pads, Nortje flicks it beautifully to the deep square leg region for a boundary.
Good length ball outside off, Nortje leaves it alone.
The batsman shows the full face of the bat and defends the ball off the back foot.
BEATEN! Beautiful from Anderson. Fullish delivery around off, Nortje looks to defend but gets squared up. He misses and the ball goes into the mitts of the keeper.

Would have been gone for all money! There was no run there but both the batters went for it. Good length ball on off, Vernon gets a thick edge towards gully and takes off for a run. Pope there dives to his right and gathers the ball. Pope throws it at the keeper's end but misses the stumps. Had he hit, Nortje would have been out by a mile. He was not even in the frame as the replays rolled in. Wondering why would Philander want to take a single off the first ball and give Nortje the strike so soon in his innings?
Fullish outside off, Anrich shoulders arms to it.
Fuller one on off, Vernon pushes it to deep cover and takes a single. Nortje has to survive one ball of Broad now.
On off, defended off the back foot.
On a length on off, Philander looks to defend but goes off the outside edge and rolls towards gully.
On a length outside off, hitting a crack on the pitch, causing it to bounce a little more. Philander looks to punch but misses it altogether due to the extra bounce on it.
BEATEN! Wild drive from Philander! Full delivery outside off, Philander looks to play an expansive drive to this one but fails to get any bat on it.
Stuart Broad to bowl from the other end.
Yes, he can! Anderson bowls a good length ball outside off, Nortje leaves this ball alone.
Anrich Nortje is the last man in and he will be facing the hat-trick ball against James Anderson. Can he survive against it?

OUT! CAUGHT! What a start to Day 3 for England! That is some bowling from James Anderson! On a length, outside off, nipping away. Rabada looks to defend this with little to no foot movement and the ball takes a faint outside edge back to Buttler who makes no mistake. Anderson appeals and the umpire raises his finger. A wicket off the last ball of Day 2 and now a wicket off the first ball on Day 3. Anderson is on fire.

We are all set to begin Day 3. Vernon Philander and the new batsman, Kagiso Rabada make their way out to the middle. They are still 54 runs behind. Can they take the lead? We will soon find out. The England players are also out in the middle. James Anderson will finish his over.

South Africa ended Day 2 on a bad note. They lost 4 wickets for 24 runs in the latter stages of the day and have Vernon Philander as the only batsman who can grind out some runs for them. They still trail by 54 runs and Philander would be hoping that the two remaining batters support him out in the middle and get the team as close to England's score. The visitors, on the other hand, would want to get the two remaining wickets as soon as possible and then swell their lead to give the home team a tough target. However, on Day 2 itself we could see some dust coming off the surface and that would be exciting for Keshav Maharaj. Both sides' batting has been average and when England come to bat, it will surely not be easy on this wicket. Stay tuned for all the action as a crucial day for both these sides lie ahead!
... Day 3, Session 1 ...

England had 1 wicket left entering into Day 2 but a set batsman as well in Ollie Pope. South Africa have 2 wickets left going into Day 3 but it is going to be Vernon Philander who has to control the batting on Sunday. Rabada and Nortje are no pushovers but they need to bat sensibly. Join us back on January 5, 2020 at 10.30 am local (0830 GMT) for all the action. ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

54 is the drift between England and South Africa at the moment. On this pitch, it looks a bit too much for the Proteas. They need to try and get as close as possible to the visitors' total and make this a one-inning shootout. Don't forget, the hosts are going to be batting last on this pitch. Would not want to chase anything above 150.

Now, to England's bowling. Cannot really criticize the bowlers. They bowled their hearts out. But Joe Root's captaincy was questionable. He just allowed the game to drift away in the second session, allowing easy singles. Then, he changed tactics in the third, stopping the runs, which eventually resulted in the flow of wickets. Anderson got 3 but the pick of the day was Stuart Broad who was relentless. Sam Curran showed the value of cutters in this format as well, getting rid of the dangerous de Kock and van der Dussen.

A reminder of the opening session, where England did not make too many runs this morning but managed to get three Protea wickets which also included that of the skipper Faf. The Saffas were in trouble at 40/3 but then Elgar, van der Dussen, Stuart Broad and Ben Stokes bailed them out. The first two forged a nice partnership, while Broad got Rassie's wicket but overstepped. Stokes, on the other hand, missed a catch of van der Dussen as well.

It was the third session on Day 1 which rocked England. It was the third session again on Day 2 which rocked the Proteas. It started with Dean Elgar, throwing his wicket out of nowhere, just like Ben Stokes did last evening. Quinton de Kock tried to play a quickfire knock, just like he did in the previous Test but he lived by the sword and died by it. He added 20 in just 26 balls but his wicket opened the floodgates. South Africa slipped from 191/5 to 215/8 in 63 balls. Advantage England.

What an action-packed day. Does anyone even remember what happened in the second session? People were yawning, shoulders were drooping, defensive fields were set and Elgar was batting. Normally, when he bats, he causes a lot of frustration to the fielding side. Because it appears as if he is being beaten but he never gets out. That second session saw 81 runs being scored without a wicket lost. At Tea, South Africa, 3 down and just 128 behind, yes, JUST 128 behind, were looking in full control to have this deficit down to 30-40 odd by Stumps. But well, this thought just jinxed them.

Whoa! What happened? What is it in that last 15 overs in the day? Day 1 saw 4 wickets fall for 13 runs in 43 balls. Day 2 sees 3 wickets fall for 15 runs in 53 balls. Dim light? Anxiety of finishing the day safely? No idea. It has hurt both teams but it is England who find themselves on top now.

OUT! CAUGHT! A wicket to end the day! That is a terrific ball. It ends a brilliant session for England. On a length on off, nipping in, Maharaj looks to flick but it goes off the inside edge onto the pads. It then lobs off to third slip where Sibley takes the catch running forward. Anderson first appeals for LBW but then sees Dominic Sibley taking the catch. He appeals again and Kumar Dharmasena, the on-field umpire gives it out signaling that it has hit the inside edge. STUMPS ON DAY 2, SA TRAIL BY 54!
Good length ball on middle and leg, Philander works it to square leg and crosses over for a single.
Outside off, left alone by Philander. 4 more balls for him to survive the day.

Well left in the end. Full delivery outside off, this one coming in. Vernon makes a good leave to that one.

Shot! Full delivery outside off, Vernon drives it through covers and picks up three before the fielder can come across and collect it before the ball reaches the ropes.
On middle, flicked to mid-wicket.

BEATEN! The new ball is doing all sorts of things out there in the middle. Beautiful bowling from Anderson. Full delivery around off swinging away. Philander looks to defend it off the front foot but misses it altogether due to the swing on it.
On off, defended out by Maharaj.
Short of a length outside off, Maharaj looks to play it at first but then decides to leave it alone.

Well played from Maharaj! Fuller one outside off, Maharaj leans forward and drives it through covers. Joe Denly hares after it and makes a sliding stop. The umpires check whether it is a clean save and the replays show that it is. Average running though. Maharaj wants the third but Philander drops his gloves at the bowler's end. So only two in the end.
BEATEN! Maharaj does not need to play at that! This is poor batting. Full delivery wide outside off, nipping away. Keshav goes on his front foot in an attempt to defend but misses it altogether.
Good length ball outside off, Maharaj lets this ball go to the keeper.

A ripper to start! Boy, is this second new ball talking or what? 3 overs and 5 balls left now for the end of day's play. Full and outside off, delivered with a scrambled seam, Maharaj pushes at it tentatively but the ball moves away, just enough, to beat the outside edge.
Stuart Broad is back on. 14-5-34-2 so far.
The batsman shows the full face of the bat and defends the ball off the back foot. The batsmen have run through for a single.

Pretorius looks to push at it but it goes off the outside edge to second slip. Stokes, ohh Stokes, drops one and takes another. He moves to his right and pouches it with both hands. This was a tough catch and Stokes has done wonderfully well. Wait, the sideways replay rolls in and it shows that Ben had caught it with just one hand. The left hand came to it late. For a change, luck favouring England.

Pretorius looks to defend but takes the outside edge going towards second slip. Stokes usually does not drop those but this one he puts one down. He bends on his knees to his left, gets two hands to it but does not hold on. Probably he was worried whether the ball will carry to him or not.
The second new ball is due now and it has been taken immediately. James Anderson is back on. 14-6-28-1, are his figures so far.

Down the leg side, Philander tucks it towards fine leg. Stuart Broad chases it down from backward square leg but then the hadada comes in his way. He tries to be cautious, fearing that the ball will hit the bird, but it calmly hops across, perfectly giving way to the ball. The crowd cheers that. A single taken.

OUT! CAUGHT! Another one bites the dust! Sam Curran does it again for England. Stokes takes a brilliant catch at second slip. Indecision costs Rassie his wicket. He is not sure whether to come forward or not but his basic foot movement is to plant his left foot forward, almost like a reflex action. Now, this is a good length ball outside off and van der Dussen has his left foot planted across. When you do that, it is very difficult to leave balls. The cherry is a touch wide but RvdD has already made up his mind to run this down to third man. Then, when he sees the line, he thinks he can leave it alone. But alas, it is too late. The ball lands and then bounces a touch high. Van der Dussen is in no man's land, just hanging his bat with its face open. The ball takes the outside edge and flies behind. Ben Stokes at slip number 2 dives to his right and takes an excellent catch with both hands. Rassie has to go after playing an excellent knock. South Africa needed him to stay till the end tonight. The deficit is reading 69 and there are still 9 overs left in the day.

Back of a length ball on middle, Philander camps on his back foot and defends it out onto the pitch.

It goes high up in the air towards mid off. James Anderson moves to his left from mid off and takes a simple catch. QdK is dejected and looks at the ground before walking off. Has this game opened up again? The deficit is 78. We might be in for a shout regarding a one-inning shootout.

OUT! CAUGHT! Ho ho ho! Are we dreaming? No, we are not! A wicket indeed has fallen. And this time, IT IS NOT A NO BALL. A poor shot from Elgar. Very rarely do we see him doing this but he has thrown it away after playing an excellent innings. He and van der Dussen were running away with the game and this might just bring the visitors back in it. Bess floats this one up outside off, Elgar strides forward and looks to lift it over mid off. However, the ball is not that full to be hit on the rise. He is already through his shot and there is extra bounce on that one. Hence, he does not time it well and it goes high up in the air. Root moves back from mid off and takes the catch. Not easy to catch those. A 100 was there for the taking for Elgar but it was not to be. Elgar is disappointed and looks up to the skies as trudges back to the pavillion. So what is the deficit? 112. Can England get another before it trickles into double digits? Sorry, cannot say trickles. Because the man coming in next will not allow the run rate to trickle down.

We are back for the final session of the day. South Africa are going along nicely and they will look to get closer to the lead. Dean Elgar and Rassie van der Dussen make their way out to the middle. The England players are also out in the ground. Can England pick up further wickets? Dominic Bess will start after the break.
... Day 2, Session 3 ...
33 overs are left in the day. Can England at least break this stand? Join us back at 3.30 pm local (1330 GMT).

Paras 2 and 3 were all South Africa. Now, England. Is everything lost? Do they get the feeling that the whole world is against them? Luck not going their way, catches not being taken... wickets not coming... what do they do? BELIEVE. Just do a bit of a flashback and check what happened last evening. The bowling has not been bad that much but the patience is being tested. South Africa were enormously patient on Friday and were rewarded. England just need to hang around. But yes, they need to stop those silly easy singles. Just too many easy runs on offer.

Gritty. Ugly. Awkward. That is Dean Elgar's defense. But who would care if he is scoring runs? He has hung in there, seen three partners walk off, got some blows on his body but has been undeterred. He has reached 77 now and his century might go a long way in South Africa getting a sizeable lead. The deficit is 128 now - so a good session should see the Saffas reduce it down to the 40s at least by Stumps.

When the rub of the green goes your way, you get all kinds of luck. Rassie van der Dussen is experiencing that at the moment. First, he got a reprieve by a Stuart Broad no ball on 16. Then, he survived a dropped catch by Ben Stokes on 43. He has soldiered on to 46 and will be determined to make the most of his luck now.

A session which could have gone England's way. A session which should have gone England's way. But due to their own mistake, they find it going to their opponents. This is a sort of wicket where one brings two and the visitors did get three quickly in the first session. But in the second, when they got Rassie van der Dussen caught behind, Broad had overstepped and since then, luck has gone against them.
