Back of a length on off, Elgar punches it to backward point and crosses over for a single.
On a length on off, Elgar pushes it to deep cover and will keep strike for the next over.
On off, defended to mid off.
FOUR! Valiant effort from Denly! Short of a length delivery down the leg side, Elgar just helps it on its way to fine leg. Denly comes across, dives but in the end the ball touches the ropes.
Fullish on middle, Elgar defends it back to the bowler.
Good length ball on middle, Elgar works it to mid-wicket.
Broad returns with a full delivery on off, Rassie pushes it to cover and crosses over for a single.
Stuart Broad will bowl from the other end. 6-4-12-2 are his figures.
On off, Dean defends it out.
Back of a length on off, Elgar taps it to gully.
FOUR! That is a fine, fine shot from Elgar. Curran dishes a half volley on middle, Elgar prods forward and creams the drive through mid on for the first boundary of the session.
Fullish on off, Elgar lunges forward and pushes it to cover.
Good length on middle, Elgar works it to backward square leg and picks up a couple.
Curran starts with a full delivery on middle, Elgar pushes it down to mid on.

The second session is all set to begin! Dean Elgar and Rassie van der Dussen make their way out to the middle to resume their innings. They still trail by 209 runs. The England players are also making their way out. Sam Curran will start for the visitors. Bowled just three overs in the first session.
... Day 2, Session 2 ...

South Africa, on the other hand, got the last wicket quickly but did not do justice with the bat at all. After a decent start from the openers, Pieter Malan was the first one to fall playing a shot to a one which he could left alone. Hamza and du Plessis soon followed him and the hosts were in tatters early on in the innings. They could have lost Rassie too but he survived due to an inside edge. Elgar has looked good and with van der Dussen, he will look to consolidate and stitch a big partnership. England though would look to bowl them out and get a big lead. What will happen? Will the Proteas fight back or will the visitors continue to chip away at the wickets? Join us in a while to find out.

England's session by a mile. They could not add much to their overnight score of 262/9 but their bowlers have been excellent in reply. They came out with a mission in hand and that was to pick up as many wickets as they can. Broad and Anderson did just that. The former started the procession with two quick wickets of Pieter Malan and Zubayr Hamza. Anderson then joined the party picking up the all-important wicket of Faf du Plessis. They could have had another wicket but an inside edge saved Rassie van der Dussen.
Full one outside off, Rassie van der Dussen lets the ball go to the keeper. LUNCH ON DAY 2.
On a length outside off, van der Dussen leaves it alone.
On middle, flicked to deep mid-wicket and a couple is taken before the fielder can clean it up.
BEATEN! What a ball from Stokes! Fuller one in the channel of uncertainty, moves away. Rassie looks to defend but misses it altogether.
Fuller one outside off, Rassie shoulders arms to this one.
Stokes starts with a good length ball on off, van der Dussen defends it off the back foot.
Ben Stokes is introduced into the attack.
Floats this one up on off, Elgar defends it out to point.
Flat one on middle and leg, van der Dussen works it to square leg and crosses over for a single.
Looped up ball on middle and leg, Rassie defends it to short leg.
Fullish on middle, Elgar plays it down to long on for a single.
On off, defended off the front foot to cover.
Flatter one on middle, Elgar works it to the leg side.
Good length on middle, Elgar works it to the leg side and picks up a single.
On off, defended to cover.
The batsman has driven it through mid off.
Full delivery on off, pushed through covers for a couple.
Good length ball on off, Rassie pushes it to point and takes a single.

NOT OUT! Rassie van der Dussen is survived by a big inside edge. Full delivery on middle, van der Dussen looks to push but misses to get hit on the pads. There were two noises though. Anderson and the rest appeal. The umpire agrees and gives it out. Rassie has gone for the DRS straightaway. The Ultra Edge rolls in and it shows that there was an inside edge. The umpire will have to overturn his decision. Brilliant to review the on-field call. Had he missed, it would have been plumb.
Rassie van der Dussen. has been given out LBW and he has reviewed it immediately. If Rassie has not hit it, he is plumb. Let's see what happens.
On middle, Elgar solidly defends it back to the bowler.
Floated on off, pushed to cover for a single.
Flatter one on middle, van der Dussen defends it to short leg.
Looped up ball on off, Rassie prods forward and defends it out.
Fuller one on middle and leg, Elgar pushes it down to long on for a single.
Flatter one outside off, Elgar leaves it alone.
Fullish ball outside off, van der Dussen makes a good leave to the keeper.
Fuller one outside off, Rassie lunges and then decides to leave the ball alone.
Good length ball on off, Rassie guides it to point.
Outside off, left alone.

BEATEN! That is a peach of a delivery. Good length delivery around off, moving away from the batsman. Rassie attempts to defend but it just whizzes past the outside edge of the bat and into the keeper's gloves.
Fullish delivery on off, Rassie defends it to cover.
Tosses this one up on middle, Elgar gently pushes it back to the bowler.
On off, Dean defends it off the back foot.
Looped up ball outside off, Elgar pushes it to cover.
Flat one on off, Elgar rocks back and blocks it to cover.
Flatter delivery on middle and leg, van der Dussen works it to deep square leg and takes a single. 50 up for the Proteas.
Loopy delivery on off, Elgar pushes it to cover and picks up a single.
Full delivery on off, van der Dussen defends it to the off side.
Good length delivery on middle, Rassie defends it to short leg.
On a length outside off, this time van der Dussen shoulders arms to it.

EDGY FOUR! Things are happening here at Newlands. Fortunate way to get off the mark for van der Dussen. Back of a length ball outside off, Rassie pokes at it but gets a thick outside edge which goes between the second slip and the gully fielder. Stokes dives to his right but the ball goes quickly past him and into the fence.
Back of a length ball outside off, Rassie does not fiddle with it and lets it through to the keeper.
On a length outside off, moving in a bit. van der Dussen leaves it alone.
Looped up ball on middle, Elgar pushes it back to Bess.
Flatter delivery on middle, Dean works it to mid-wicket.
On middle, played back to the bowler.
Floated ball on middle, Elgar works it to the leg side and says no for the single.
Loopy delivery on middle, Dean defends it out.

FOUR! UPPISH BUT SAFE! Bess starts with a floated ball outside off, Elgar lunges forward and looks to drive but it goes uppishly. Luckily for Elgar it goes wide of the diving fielder and into the extra cover fence. Not sure whether the fielder got his hand on it.
First signs of spin! Dominic Bess is into the attack.
On a length on middle, Rassie defends it out. Excellent over comes to an end from James Anderson.
Rassie van der Dussen is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Anderson returns and picks up the big fish, the South African skipper. Excellent bowling. Full delivery around off, du Plessis looks to defend but it takes the outside edge and goes to second slip. Stokes stationed there moves to his left and takes a simple catch. The hosts slip further. 40 for 3 in no time. Not the start South Africa would have wanted.
Good length outside off, du Plessis shoulders arms to this one.
Good length delivery with extra bounce. Faf looks to defend but it hits the splice of the bat and rolls onto the pitch.
On a length on middle, du Plessis blocks it back to the bowler.
Full delivery on middle, Faf defends it to mid on off the front foot.
James Anderson is back on.
On off, pushed to point for nothing.
On a length on off, Elgar defends it to cover.
Short of a length on middle, Faf works it to square leg and crosses over for a single.
Good length ball on middle, du Plessis defends it out to Curran.
Back of a length ball outside off, Elgar pushes it to deep point and takes a single.
Nicely bowled! Well played too. Very full delivery on middle, Elgar gets his bat down in time and blocks it out.
Good length ball on off, du Plessis blocks it out.
Outside off, left alone.
Fullish delivery outside off, Faf lets the ball go to the keeper.
On a length on off, Faf stands tall and defends it to point.
Very full delivery on middle, du Plessis pushes it down to mid on.
Good length ball outside off, Faf makes a good leave to this one.
On a length on middle, Elgar works it to mid-wicket.
Fullish one on middle, Dean pushes it to mid off.
Good length on off, Elgar blocks it out to cover off the back foot.
On off, Elgar is solid in defense.
Fuller one on off, Dean blocks it out to point.
Good length on middle and leg, Elgar defends it to mid on.
Good length ball on middle, Faf defends it back to the bowler. Broad shows some aggression as he picks the ball and underarms the ball towards du Plessis. Stares exchanged.

Drinks! A brilliant hour for England then. After bundling out quickly, they have removed two Protea batters inside 10 overs. It is Stuart Broad who is doing the damage. Elgar has looked solid but his partners, not so good so far. Here's his skipper Faf du Plessis coming in to join him out in the middle. Can these two occupy the crease and build a decent stand together? An intriguing hour awaits.

OUT! CAUGHT! Excellent catch from Stokes and Broad gets his second wicket. South Africa are in a spot of bother. Back of a length ball outside off, nipping away. Hamza looks to defend it off the back foot but gets a thick outside edge towards second slip. Stokes there, dives to his right and pouches it just inches above the ground. Brilliant. Broad is making the ball talk from his end at Newlands.
Stuart Broad has got an official warning for running on the danger area. First one of the innings.
On a length on off, nipping in. Hamza defends it out solidly.
On off, driven towards mid off where the fielder dives and stops the ball. No run.
Good length ball on middle, Zubayr defends it out off the back foot.

FOUR! Brilliant shot from Hamza! Positive cricket! That's how he likes to play. Full delivery on off, Hamza leans forward and creams the drive through the cover region for a boundary. Stokes chases after it but does not manage to get there in time.
Full ball outside the off stump line, Dean lets the ball go to the keeper.
Fullish delivery on middle, Elgar works it to mid-wicket.
On off, Zubayr gets off the mark by guiding this towards point and taking a single.
Better from Curran! Good length ball outside off, Hamza leaves it alone.

Another one down the leg side, Elgar flicks it to the deep mid-wicket region and takes three before Crawley from deep square leg hares across and collects it. 7 from the first two balls to start with from Curran.
FOUR! Curran starts with a poor delivery on the pads, Elgar whips it away to the deep mid-wicket region for a boundary. The fielder from deep square leg comes across but gives up the chase.
First change from England. Sam Curran is brought into the attack. He picked up four wickets in the first innings of the first Test. Can he make an impact here as well?

BEATEN! Excellent. Just excellent stuff from Broad. Good length ball outside off, moving away from the batsman. Hamza looks to defend off the back foot but fails to get anything on it. A successful over comes to an end from Broad.
On off, Hamza pushes it back to Broad.
Length ball on off, Zubayr looks to defend but it goes off the outside edge towards gully who collects it on a bounce.
Good length ball on middle and leg, Hamza defends it out to mid on.
Fuller ball around off, Hamza comes forward and keeps it out.
Zubayr Hamza is the new man in.

OUT! Caught! Broad strikes and the debutant has to depart! Brilliant bowling from him. A slightly shortish ball outside off which shapes away after pitching. He can easily let this go to the keeper but this time he has a poke at it. The away movement means an outside edge is induced and it goes to Root at first slip. He takes it in front of his face nicely. Poor, poor shot this one from the debutant.

EDGY FOUR! Just short! Good length ball on off, nipping away, Elgar looks to defend it but gets squared up. It goes off the outside edge towards first slip. It bounces in front of him and goes between his legs into the fence.
Length ball on middle and leg, Elgar works it to deep square leg and picks up a couple.
Fuller ball on off, Elgar solidly defends it back to the bowler.
On a length on off, Elgar blocks it off the back foot to point.
Fullish delivery outside off, Dean shoulders arms to this one.
Good length ball on off, Elgar defends it to mid off.
Another leave to see off the over as Broad dishes out another good length ball outside off.
In the channel again but too wide to make Malan play. He shoulders arms.
Outside off this time, an easy leave for Malan.
Another ball around off on a fullish length, Malan pushes it to point.
Beauty from Broad! Fuller and just outside off. As Malan comes forward to defend the ball shapes away from his and bat. Luckily for him, it does not take the outside edge.
Good length ball on middle, blocked towards mid-wicket.
Nicely done! A fuller ball around off, Elgar runs it down through point and gully and before the fielder can get to the ball, a couple for him.
Around off, pushed to point.
On middle, Elgar pushes it to mid on.
Good length ball on off, Elgar waits and at the last moment taps it towards gully where the fielder does well to stop the ball with a tumble to his left.
Fuller and on middle, Elgar works it in front of square leg.
Good length ball on middle, worked towards square leg by Malan for a single.
Fuller and on off this time, Elgar looks to drive but gets an inside edge. The ball goes between his legs but luckily does not go onto the stumps.
Another one on off, Elgar once again makes a solid block.
This one is pitched on off and it comes into Elgar. He blocks it off the back foot.
He does that on this one. Bowls it around off and on a slightly fuller length, Elgar gets behind the line of the delivery and defends.
Another ball which is outside off, Elgar has nothing to do with it once again. Broad needs to get closer to the off pole and make Elgar play.
Shortish length ball outside off, Elgar makes a leave to start the over.
Gets slightly fuller and around off, Malan this time comes forward and defends it.
Make that third leave in a row as Malan once again covers his stumps and allows the ball to go to the keeper.
Another leave as Anderson bowls it on a good length ball outside off.
In the channel outside off, it is left alone.
Good length around off, tapped towards covers.
Outside off, Malan covers his stumps and lets it go to the keeper.
FOUR! This is a brilliant shot! Full and outside off, Elgar reaches out and drives it through point for another boundary.

FOUR BYES! That's through everyone. A good length ball which is once again angled into Elgar. He looks to defend but the ball comes back in sharply to beat his inside edge. Buttler behind the wicket fails to collect the ball either. It goes behind him and into the fence.
Landed around off on a good length, Elgar looks to defend but the ball takes the inner half of the bat and goes to square leg.
Good length ball outside off, it is angled into the left-hander. Elgar covers his stumps and shoulders arms.
FOUR! Punched nicely! First one from Elgar's bat. Another fuller ball around off, Elgar just punches it on the front foot. It races to the long off fence in a jiffy.
Fuller ball on off first up from Broad. Elgar leans and pushes it to mid off.
Stuart Broad with the ball from the other end. 2 slips and a gully for him.

FOUR! First runs for Pieter Malan in Test cricket! This will give him a lot of confidence. Short delivery outside off, Malan stands tall and punches it through the cover region for a boundary. Gives a smile after hitting that shot.
Fullish ball nipping away, Pieter leaves the ball alone to the keeper.
Full delivery on middle, Malan defends his first ball in international cricket back to the bowler.
South Africa and Elgar are underway! Fuller one outside off, Elgar pushes it through covers and crosses over for a single.
Back of a length ball on off, Elgar defends it out to point.
Anderson starts with a good length ball on middle, Elgar defends it out to mid off.

Now, 438 is the target for South Africa. How will they approach it? Well, chasing this total is as good as climbing the Mount Everest. However, let's rewind the clock a bit. Remember the historic Johannesburg ODI? Chasing 435, South Africa had scored 438. What a game that was. While this is a Test match and it is not going to be easy. But remember, nothing is impossible in cricket. However, honestly, one would feel that they will try to play session by session and then plan accordingly. England, on the other hand, would be keen to bundle the Proteas and level the series. The final innings of the Test will start in a while.

The day started with Stokes going bonkers straightaway. A 47-ball 72 means that England scored runs at a very brisk pace. Sibley, on the other hand, calmly raked up his maiden Test ton to push England towards a massive lead. Approach from Faf du Plessis looked very defensive and once Stokes started pouncing, he went further into the shell and it looked like he was just trying to buy more time. After the wicket of Stokes, Maharaj struck again with Nortje picking one too. One would feel that they came a little too late.

The declaration was coming and now it has come. Sensible call this from the England skipper. He would not want his fast bowlers to get injured on the bouncers of Rabada. Once again it is Dominic Sibley who leads his partner as he goes back to the pavilion. He gets a standing ovation from the crowd for his brilliant unbeaten ton.
Drops just short! Floated on middle, Broad gets on his knees to sweep this one but gets a top edge towards long on. The fielder from there comes after it but it falls way short. Two taken.
On middle, Sibley plays the reverse sweep to cover and a single is taken.
Fullish down the leg side, Sibley paddle sweeps but finds the short fine leg fielder.
Tossed up ball outside off, Broad bends and plays it down to long on for another run.
On middle and leg, Sibley sweeps it to backward square leg for a single.
FOUR! Innovation from Sibley! Flighted ball on middle, Sibley reverse sweeps it through fine leg for a boundary. Dean Elgar chases after it from point but gives up the chase.
Safe!!! Short of a length delivery on middle, Broad hops in an attempt to defend but gets hit on the splice of the bat. It lobs towards short leg but it falls just wide of him.
OHH! Short ball around the leg stump line, Broad looks to flick it but gets hit on the gloves and rolls to square leg. Broad wants the single but is not there.
BOUNCER! It is around middle and leg, Broad attempts the pull shot but fails to get any bat on it.
On a length outside off, Sibley guides it down to third man for a single.
Good length ball on middle, Dominic works it to mid-wicket. Stokes signals to Sibley from the dressing room to attack a little more.
Full on off, Sibley pushes it to mid off.

The declaration looks very close by. James Anderson, Joe Root, Ben Stokes and the England coach are having a word in the dressing room. They all look ready and it also looks like Anderson is not even padded up.
The batsman works it down the leg side.
Tossed up ball around off, Broad looks to sweep but gets hit on the pads. There is a slight appeal for LBW but not given by the umpire.
BEATEN! Flatter one outside off, Broad looks to play it nice and fine on the off side but missed it altogether.
PLAY AND A MISS! Floated on off, Stuart looks to sweep but fails to get any bat on it.
Flatter on off, Broad defends it out to the slip cordon. He wants the single but is sent back.
FOUR! Very well played. Floated out off, Broad premeditates the sweep and hits it fine down the leg side. Elgar gives it a chase but gives up halfway as he knows he has no chance reaching that.
Good length delivery outside off, Sibley defends it towards point.
Full on off, Dominic pushes it to mid on.
Full on off, Sibley pushes it to mid on.
A big cheer from the English fans as Broad gets off the mark. Back of a length on middle, Broad hops up and dabs it to the off side and scampers to the other end.
Full on off, Sibley looks to push it straight but it goes off the outer half of his bat through cover-point for a single. First run of the session for England and Sibley.
Back of a length on off, Sibley defends it off the back foot.
Kagiso Rabada to bowl from the other end. 18-3-66-2 so far from him.

Good fielding from the substitute fielder, Keegan Petersen. Floated on leg, Broad gets down on one knee and sweeps it to the left of backward square leg. Petersen there dives to that side and saves runs for his side.
Floated on middle and leg, Broad looks to defend but the ball goes away down the leg side.
Around the pads, Broad paddles it behind square on the leg side.
Stuart Broad is in at 10.

OUT! Caught! South Africa strike in the first over of the second session itself. Not the best of balls from Maharaj and he knows he is lucky to get a wicket of this delivery. A drag down on middle, Curran goes on his back foot and looks to pull it over mid-wicket. He cannot get under it and he is unable to get the desired elevation. It goes towards short mid-wicket where Zubayr Hamza takes a good catch, low to the ground. Now can South Africa bowl England out under 450?
On off, pushed back to the bowler.
Beaten! A flatter ball outside off, Curran pokes at it to get beaten.

The second session is set to get underway!!! The South African players make their way out to the field. Dominic Sibley and Sam Curran also walk out to the middle with England leading by 421. How many runs will they add to this lead? Keshav Maharaj to start the session with the ball.
... Day 4, Afternoon Session ...

So England are comfortably in the driver's seat and are in a position to call all the shots in this game. They have been aggressive in their approach and one will feel they will continue more of the same in the second session. It will be interesting to see how long they continue to bat if they are not bowled out. South Africa, on the other hand, need to find some inspiration and motivation. And rather than wait for England to declare they should try and bowl them out quickly and carry some momentum before they walk out to bat. What will happen? Join us after the break for the second session to find out.

It has been an abject performance by South Africa. They were defensive from the start and have paid the full price for it. Rather than attacking and trying to take wickets, they have tried to stop the run flow and have been taken to the sword by the tourists. They have managed to take 3 wickets but that has come because England were throwing everything at it. Keshav Maharaj has bowled from one end throughout the session and he has been taken to the cleaners. He has struggled massively and one feels he has been thrown under the bus. There was a little bit of respite for him as he took the wicket of the dangerous Ben Stokes. Rabada and Nortje, who has been unwell picked the other two wickets to have fallen in this session. But it has been a poor performance by the Proteas in the first session.

The man who has been superb and who will never forget this day, Dominic Sibley leads his partner off the field. Brilliant session for the visitors. They have taken their lead to a massive 421 and are well and truly on top of this Test. They are not done yet either as Sam Curran and Dominic Sibley are still out in the middle. The day started with Ben Stokes going hammer and tonks. The pair of Sibley and Stokes added 92 off just 103 with the all-rounder scoring 72 off just 47 balls. Sibley continued his overnight's good work and is still unbeaten there on 125. Buttler then replaced Ben and he continued from where his teammate left off. Jos though could not continue his firecrackers for long. They have scored a mammoth 157 runs in this session at an ODI run rate of 5.81.
Full on off, Dominic defends it off the front foot. LUNCH ON DAY 4.
Full delivery on off, Curran plays it towards long on. Rabada comes across from long on quickly but does not collect cleanly. Only a single though.
Short of a length outside off, Curran punches it towards the deep point region. The fielder from deep cover comes across, slides and stops the ball. The batters take two.
On middle, defended off the back foot to the bowler.

OUCH! That mush have hurt! Short delivery on middle and leg, Curran looks to fend it away awkwardly but gets hit on the gloves. The ball lobs off towards the leg side. England will hope that Curran is not hurt badly as it is his bowling hand.
FOUR! Pulled away handsomely! Short of a length ball on middle, Curran pulls it through deep square leg for a boundary. Second one for him in this innings.
Dwaine Pretorius is back on. Might be the last over before Lunch.
Floated on off, Sibley defends it out.
Tossed up on middle, flicked to the leg side for a single.
On middle, worked to square leg.
Flatter one on middle, Sam pushes it back to the bowler.
FOUR! Sam Curran joins the party! That is some shot from Curran. Maharaj dishes a half volley outside off, Curran leans forward and slams it through the cover region for a boundary.
Flighted on the pads, Sibley tucks it to square leg and takes a quick single.
Much better from Nortje! Short ball around off, Sam sways away from it. End of a successful over from Nortje.
FOUR BYES! This is poor bowling! Giving easy runs to England. A bouncer around middle, very high though. Curran ducks under it. De Kock jumps to collect but it goes over and into the fence.
On off, pushed to cover and collects a single.
BOUNCER! It is bowled around off, Sibley sway away from it.
Good length ball on off, Curran pushes it to deep cover to get off the mark.
Sam Curran comes in to replace Buttler.

OUT! CAUGHT! Buttler tries an innovative shot but fails! No excitement shown by the Proteas as they know that they have backs to the wall. Good length ball on off, Buttler tries to play the scoop shot but it takes the gloves and goes to the keeper who collects with utmost ease. Buttler starts walking without even the umpire raising his finger. Buttler goes but not before playing a very handy cameo.
Down the leg side, padded away by Sibley.
FOUR! Nice touch! Floated on the pads, Sibley tucks it nicely past the diving short fine leg fielder and into the fence. England's lead moves past 400.
On the pads, flicked to the leg side.
Almost! That is close! Very full delivery down the leg side, Sibley looks to sweep but misses. It almost brushes the leg stump and goes to the keeper. Sibley tumbles after that shot.
Floated on the pads, Sibley goes on his front foot and defends it out.
Very full delivery down the leg side, Sibley looks to flick but misses it completely.
Short again, pulled again. This time the deep square leg fielder does well to stop the ball with a slide. But he cannot stop another couple of runs for Buttler.
Another couple and this brings up the 350 for England. A back of a length ball on middle, Buttler pulls it wide of the deep square leg fielder and runs an easy two.
Good length ball around off, driven through covers and another easy couple for Buttler.
Shortish and outside off, Buttler taps it through point for a couple of runs.
SIX! Hammered! Second biggie off Buttler's bat now. A back of a length ball on off, Buttler goes on the back foot and slams it sailing over the deep square leg fence for half a dozen more
Good length ball around off, it is defended.
On the pads, Sibley this time pads it away.
FOUR! Superb placement. Now a fuller ball from Maharaj down the leg side, Sibley sweeps it towards fine leg. There's no protection in the deep and the ball rolls to the fence. Easy runs these.
Flatter one on off, Sibley goes back to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.

SIX! Massive! Enough of blocking from Sibley as he gets into the zone now. A flighted ball in the slot of Sibley. He gets down on one knee and mows it over deep mid-wicket for a biggie. First one of his innings.
Flatter one on the pads, worked behind square leg for a run.
Down the leg side. No spin at all. Buttler looks to flick but misses.
Landed around off, pushed towards point.
On the pads, Sibley flicks towards mid-wicket and thinks for a single but the fielder there makes a sliding stop.
WIDE! For height it is. An effort ball from Nortje as he bends his back and bowls a short of length ball outside off. Sibley lets it be as it goes well over his head.
Shortish around off, tapped through point for a single.

SIX! Wow! Just the extension of the arms and it flies over long off. Brilliant timing. Nortje overpitches it outside off, Buttler gets to the pitch of the ball and meets the ball on the full nicely. He just non-nonchalantly lofts it over long off for a biggie.
Around off on a shortish length. Blocked.

Nortje starts his spell with a fuller ball around off, Sibley pushes it towards point and takes off for a quick single. The point fielder throws the ball at the non-striker's end after picking the ball quickly but he misses. Would not have mattered though as Sibley was in.
Anrich Nortje into the attack. First time on Day 4. He did not take the field early on as he was unwell and looking at his face, it clearly looks like he is feeling uneasy.
The batsman shows the full face of the bat and defends the ball off the back foot.
Outside off, pushed to mid off.
Flatter one on middle, Sibley easily nudges it to fine leg for a single.
Full and on the pads again, Buttler misses the sweep again. The ball hits the pads and rolls towards square leg. A leg bye taken.
Flatter one around off, it is defended.
Fuller ball the pads, Buttler looks to paddle sweep it but misses.
On middle, Buttler works it to the leg side for a single.
Jos Buttler joins Sibley out in the middle now. He is an aggressive player. What will be his approach?

OUT! CHOPPED ON! Pope fails to repeat his heroics from the first innings! Two quick wickets for South Africa and this might help them to build some much-needed momentum here. Good length ball outside off, it keeps a bit low off the deck. Pope, who is a good off side player, looks to play it on the off side but fails to go fully with a horizontal bat. He ends up playing a shot with a half-vertical and a half-horizontal bat. He ends up getting an inside edge and the ball goes onto uproot the leg pole. England lead by 360. South Africa will now look to wrap it up under 400!
On a length on off, Pope pushes it to cover.
On middle, worked to mid-wicket and takes a single.
Good length ball on off, Pope guides it through gully and takes a single. He wants the second but it is not there as the fielder gets to it quickly.
Back of a length ball on off, Pope defends it out off the back foot.

Looped up ball down the leg side, Pope flicks it to square leg where Rabada misfields and allows the ball to go towards the deep. Two taken before Philander comes across from fine leg and collects it.
Fullish down the leg side, Pope pads this one away.
Flatter one on middle and leg, Sibley works it to the leg side for a single.
On middle, Pope reverse sweeps it to deep cover for a single.
Floated on middle, Pope defends it to mid-wicket.
Ollie Pope walks in next.

OUT! CAUGHT! An excellent hand from Ben Stokes comes to an end.  He has taken England to a very healthy lead in very quick time. He was putting on a show out there and was on his way to a quickfire century but it has been cut short. Maharaj who has had a torrid time with the ball finally has something to cheer about. Floated delivery around off, Stokes once again goes for the big slog sweep. He does not connect it well and the bat also turns in his hand. It goes to the right of long on. Rassie van der Dussen moves on that side and takes a good catch. It looked easy but it was not an easy one to take as the ball was hit with power and it was rushing onto him. Stokes walks out to a standing ovation from the crowd. Finally the hosts have something to smile about this morning but is it too late already?
Bumper on middle. Sibley easily ducks under it.
In the channel outside off, Sibley is not affected from Stokes hammering from the other end as he calmly lets the ball go to the keeper.
Back of a length ball on off, Stokes pulls it to long on for a single.
Good length ball on off, pushed to sweeper cover by Sibley this time.
Short and outside off, Stokes slaps it to sweeper cover for a single.
Swing and a miss! A good length ball outside off, Stokes looks to tonk it over long off but misses.
Floated ball down the leg side, Sibley pads this one away.
Low full toss on middle, Stokes comes down and pushes it down to long on for a single.

FOUR! Some innovation time from Ben! Brilliant. Floated ball on middle, Stokes plays the reverse sweep towards the deep point region for a boundary. 14 already from the over. Are England looking to declare soon?
SIX! Bang! That is hit a long way. Stokes is on fire at the moment. Flighted ball on middle, Stokes dances down the track and hammers it over the bowler's head for a biggie.
FOUR! Bisects the two fielders perfectly. Short delivery this time on middle, Stokes pulls it in front of square and bisects the two fielders and goes into the fence.
PLAY AND A MISS! Misses out! Maharaj tosses this one up, landing it on the rough outside off and keeping a little low. Stokes looks to msweep but fails to get any bat on it.

Drinks Break! No prizes for guessing who the first hour of Day 4 belonged to. Stokes has got to his fifty, Sibley has got to his maiden ton and the English lead has ballooned up to 338. They are well and truly on top of this game and are going all guns blazing. South Africa look like a tamed lion at the moment and look out of sorts here. They have been trying to put a brake on the run flow rather than taking wickets but are struggling to contain as well. The game is slipping away from them and they need to find a way to put some sort of pressure on the visitors.
Full delivery outside off, Sibley leaves the ball alone.
Short delivery on off, Stokes punches it straight past the bowler and calls Sibley for a couple but decides against it as the long off fielder comes across quickly and cleans it up.
On a length on middle, Sibley works it to deep square leg and takes a run.
Edged but short! Good length ball on off, with some extra bounce. Sibley looks to defend but it takes the outside edge and goes on one bounce to gully.
Back of a length delivery outside off, Dominic looks to play at it first but then decides to leave the ball alone.
Fullish delivery on off, Stokes pushes it down to long off for a single.
Fullish down the leg side, Sibley calmly pads this one away.

FOUR! CENTURY! Maiden Test ton for Dominic Sibley! A moment he, his family and all his friends will cheer and relish for the rest of his life. What a gem of a knock this has been from Sibley. Tossed up on the pads, Sibley gets down on one knee and sweeps it through backward square leg for a boundary to reach the milestone. All the English fans and his teammates are on their feet applauding the efforts of this young man. He removes his helmet, raises it along with his bat and has a huge smile on his face. He deserves all the applaud he is getting as he has put his side in a commendable position in this game.
Down the leg side, padded away. Faf at leg slip dives to his right and cleans it up.
Flatter one down the leg side, Sibley is in no hurry to get to his hundred as he pads this away.
On off, pushed down to long on for a single.
Flatter delivery outside off, Stokes punches it through covers and collects a couple before the fielder comes across and clean it up.

EDGY FOUR! Moves to 99 with a lucky boundary. Good length delivery on off, Sibley attempts to defend but gets squared up. It takes the outside edge and goes between the gully and the second slip fielders for a boundary.
Outside off, left alone by Dominic.
Full delivery on off, Sibley looks to flick but gets a leading edge which rolls towards the off side.
Good length delivery on off, Dominic defends it to the bowler.
On a length on middle, Sibley defends it out to mid off.

FIFTY! 21st Test fifty for Stokes. He has been positive since he came out to bat and has got to the milestone in just 34 balls. He gets there by pulling this short delivery to fine leg and taking a single. He definitely loves playing at this ground.
Another ball has been padded away by Sibley.
Full and on the pads of Stokes, he easily works it towards mid-wicket for a single. Maharaj has conceded 100 runs without picking a wicket now in this innings.
Outside off on a fuller length, Stokes reverse sweeps it to deep point. A couple of easy runs for Stokes as Rabada from sweeper cover makes a sliding stop.
On the leg pole again, an easy flicked single towards square leg for Sibley.
On the pads, it is padded away by Sibley.
Flatter one this time, turning into the left-hander. Stokes tucks it towards square leg for a single.
On a length on middle, Dominic defends it out. 11 from Rabada's first over on Day 4.

FOUR! Good length ball outside off, Sibley drives it through covers and is racing away to the fence. Dean Elgar runs across from deep cover and slides to make a stop. The umpire goes in to check whether it is a clean save but Elgar's leg has touched the ropes. England have crossed their first innings score and that too with six wickets in hand.

Short of a length ball on middle, Stokes pulls it to deep square leg for a single. 50-run stand is also up between the two. This has been an attacking stand especially Stokes. They are going after the bowlers and are batting South Africa out of the game.
FOUR! Brilliant shot from Stokes! He is on a rampage here. Full toss on middle, Stokes hammers it over the mid-wicket region for a boundary.

TOP EDGE BUT SAFE! Luck favouring Stokes here! Short of a length ball on middle, Stokes looks to pull it but it goes off the top edge. The fine leg fielder is running ahead but stops as he sees Quinton de Kock  signaling that it is his catch. De Kock dives but fails to get any hand on it as well. There is a lot of breeze blowing around the ground and that may have taken it away from the keeper.
Rabada starts with a length ball on middle, Stokes defends it off the back foot to mid-wicket.
Kagiso Rabada is into the attack for the first time on Day 4. He replaces Vernon Philander, strange choice this as one would have expected him to replace Keshav Maharaj.
On the pads, Sibley defends it to get through the over.
Darts on the pads, Sibley pads it away.
Maharaj comes over the wicket and bowls on the pads. Sibley glances it through mid-wicket and gets a couple to get into the nervous 90s.
Now goes around off, DS defends it towards cover-point.
Slightly shorter on off, Dominic defends it off the back foot.
Floated on off, Sibley gets on his front foot and defends it.
Short of a length outside off, Ben comes down the track and looks to cut but it takes the bottom edge and goes towards the keeper.
FOUR! Stokes is latching onto Philander here. Short delivery outside off, Stokes stands tall and slams it through backward point for a boundary.
Length ball outside off, Stokes looks to drive but gets a top edge. Luckily for him, it lands safely and goes towards deep cover. Two taken. The lead goes past 300.

FOUR! Beautiful shot! It is not a bad ball from Philander though. Low full toss on middle, Stokes whips it towards deep square leg. Elgar runs across from deep mid-wicket, dives to stop but fails to do so. It rolls into the fence.
Fullish on off, Sibley pushes it wide of mid off for a single.
Goes for the attacking option! Fullish delivery on middle, Stokes dances down the track and looks to heave it away but gets an inside edge which goes deep mid-wicket. a single taken.
Loopy on off, Sibley lunges and pushes it down to mid on.
On middle, defended back to the bowler.
BEATEN! Nicely bowled! Flatter one outside off, Sibley looks to push off the back foot but misses it completely.
Full on off, Dominic plays it back to Maharaj off the front foot.
Floated outside off, Sibley leaves it alone.
Flatter one on middle, Stokes pushes it down to long on for a single.
On a length outside off, swinging away from the batsman. Sibley lets it go to the keeper to see off the over. A maiden from Philander on his return.
Length ball on middle, DS blocks it out onto the pitch.
On off, defended off the front foot to cover.
Fullish outside off, moving away, Dominic lets it through to the keeper.
Short of a length outside off, Sibley shoulders arms to this one.
Philander starts with a fuller one on middle, Sibley gets on his front foot and defends it back to the bowler.
The second new ball has been taken now. Vernon Philander is back on as well. 12-6-12-0 are his figures. Interesting to see what strategy Stokes opts now.
Floated on off, Stokes defends it to get through the over.
Once again it turns off the rough and Ben is lucky to survive that. It pitches outside off and turns in off the rough. Stokes comes across and looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the pads.
Tossed up on the rough outside off. Stokes goes for another slog sweep but the ball turns off the rough and hits Stokes on his arm.
Around the pads, Stokes tucks it through mid-wicket and gets a couple.
SIX! Stokes has demolished that ball. Floated around off, Ben gets down on one knee and smothers the ball well over the mid-wicket fence for a monstrous biggie. Ben in T20 mode here.
Floated on off, Stokes paddle sweeps it fine down the leg side for a brace.
Nortje is back on the field. Maybe now they will take the new ball sooner rather than later.
Length delivery on middle, Stokes punches it wide of mid-wicket and gets a single to keep the strike.
On a length on middle, BS glances it to mid-wicket.
Good length ball on off, Stokes defends it off his front foot.
Now Ben gets back into Test mode and blocks this off the back foot.

FOUR! Innovative from Stokes and he has connected it really well. 14 for Ben Stokes from Pretorius' last 3 deliveries. Dwaine pulls his length back and bowls it on off and middle. Stokes reverse sweeps it over the slip cordon for a boundary.
SIX! Right out of the meat of the bat. That was six the moment he hit that. Full on off, Stokes maintains his balance and smashes it straight over Pretorius' head for a biggie.
Tossed up on off, Sibley blocks it.
On the pads, Sibley once again offers no stroke and pads it away.
Floated on the pads, Sibley flicks it fine down the leg side and gets a couple. First runs off the day for Dominic.
On the pads and once again Sibley pads it away.
Once again on the pads, Sibley taps it onto the ground wide of leg slips.
On the pads from around the wicket. Sibley pads it away.
FOUR! That was going to the fence as soon as he hit it. Good length ball outside off, Stokes pulls it using the power of his bottom hand and the ball races away to the mid-wicket fence.
Back of a length around off, Stokes punches it but to mid off.
Pretorius targets the stumps. Ben blocks it with calmness.
Length delivery on off, BS defends it with a straight bat.
On the pads, Stokes looks to defend but gets hit on the pads.
Good length ball on off, Stokes defends it off the back foot.
Anrich Nortje has not taken to the field as he is unwell. Big blow for the Proteas. Also, Quinton de Kock is upto the stumps now for Pretorius.
Floated on off, Sibley defends it to get through the over.
Another one down the leg side, Sibley leaves it alone.
On the pads, Sibley leaves it alone. It kisses his pad and goes past the man at leg slip. Runs won't be counted as DS did not offer any shot.
On the pads, Sibley tickles it fine down the leg side but the man at fine leg is inside so Dominic does not get a single he is looking for.
Ben is off the mark! Tossed up around off, Stokes gets down on one knee and sweeps it towards fine leg for a single.
Flighted delivery on off, Stokes defends it off the back foot.
Second new ball available now and one would assume South Africa will take it straightaway. Faf has not opted to take it. Keshav Maharaj to bowl from the other end. 27-8-79-0 are his figures so far.
Pretorius finishes the over with a length delivery outside off. DS leaves it alone. Maiden to start the day.
Pretorius goes short for the first time. Sibley keeps his eyes on the ball and sways away from it.
Good length ball around off, Dominic defends it towards cover off his back foot.
Dwaine hits the deck hard around off, Sibley defends it with a straight bat.
Good length ball outside off, Sibley is in no hurry to score the first runs of the day and leaves it alone.
Pretorius starts with a fuller delivery around off, Sibley starts his innings with a solid front foot defense.

We are all set to begin Day 4! The South African players are in a huddle before making their way to the field. Overnight batsman, Dominic Sibley walks out to the middle with new batsman, Ben Stokes. Dwaine Pretorius to bowl from the other end.

England lead by 264 and still have 6 wickets in hand. It will be interesting to see what approach they follow and swell their lead to as much as possible. South Africa, on the other hand, struggled to pick up wickets and they would want to restrict the visitors to around 320 to have any chance in this game. So, what holds for us on Day 4? Will the Proteas make a comeback or will the visitors continue to dominate?
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

So, what holds for us on Day 4, the penultimate day of this Test match? England are right on top and they would now look to get their lead closer to 350 or more. That should be enough on this wicket given that the cracks will open up on Day 4. South Africa, on the other hand, need wickets and that too quickly. Can South Africa make a comeback in this game or will the visitors continue to be on top? Join us on Monday, 6th January at 1030 Local (0830 GMT). Until then, cheers.

South Africa, on the other hand, did not do justice with the ball. They kept on bowling poor lines and lengths which the English batters pounced upon easily. Keshav Maharaj was disappointing as his negative line approach did not work as he remained wicketless. Vernon Philander and Anrich Nortje were the pick of the bowlers though. Nortje picked up two while Philander picked up only 1 but was relentless throughout. Dwaine Pretorius removed Root late in the day to finish on a positive note.

Just like on Day 2, a wicket has fallen at the stroke of Stumps. Bess fell and the umpires call it a day. A day which has belonged to England. Yes, they lost the wicket of Joe Root and Dominic Bess in the end but not before Root had done his job. They are leading by 264 and with 6 wickets in hand, they have a chance to bat South Africa out of this game. The day started with England finishing off the hosts' tail quickly and then batters had to do the job which they did. Sibley and Crawley started well but the latter fell soon after. Denly, then joined Sibley out in the middle and stitched a good partnership. After Denly's wicket, came a match-defining partnership between Root and Sibley. They stitched a 116-run stand to put the visitors right on top. Sibley has played an excellent hand and is close to reaching his maiden Test ton.

OUT! Caught down the leg side and the nightwatchman cannot see off the day for England. Brilliant ball this one from Nortje. Bends his back and bowls a bouncer on middle and leg. Bess looks to fend it away but misses. De Kock behind the wicket pouches the ball and makes a loud appeal along with the slip cordon and the bowler. Not out says the umpire. Now, should South Africa opt for the review against the nightwatchman with just a minute left for Stumps? Well, Nortje, the bowler himself is not sure. Du Plessis and de Kock is confident though and the skipper eventually signals the 'T'. Interesting. Let's see what the replays show. Front foot is alright. Let's go to the business end now. Here comes Ultra Edge. Wow, a deflection off the gloves, detects the Ultra Edge. The umpire has to change his decision. Out it is and a very good review from South Africa. AND WITH IT, STUMPS ON DAY 3 AS WELL.

Caught down the leg side? South Africa appeal but the umpire shakes his head. Faf du Plessis and de Kock think there was a noise. Nortje is not sure but Faf opts for the review. There is some deflection. Here comes the replays. Front foot is fine. Ultra Edge comes in now. Well, well, there's a deflection as the ball goes past the gloves. Out it is then.
Shortish ball around middle, Bess this time stands tall and taps it onto the pitch.
That's a good leave! A good length ball angled into the right-hander. Bess covers his stumps and shoulders arms.
On off, a solid defensive stroke from Bess now.
Bangs this one short and angles it in. Well, that's all right but the line is not right as it lands on middle and leg and goes down the leg side as Bess ducks under it easily.
Full delivery on middle, Bess defends it out off the front foot.
Anrich Nortje is back on.

That took off! Probably due to one of those cracks. Pretorius bowls it on a length outside off, it pitches and takes off. De Kock moves to his left to collect the ball but it hits his fingers and goes behind. A bye stolen by the batters.
Fullish and around off, Bess gets behind the line of it and defends it.
Yes, nightwatchman it is. Dominic Bess walks out with around 9 minutes left for Stumps. Can he survive these tricky few overs?

OUT! CAUGHT! Root cannot believe it. Pretorius does the trick. Good length ball on off, hitting a crack around the off stump. It moves away a little. Root looks to defend it of the front foot but gets a thick outside edge which goes towards first slip. Faf du Plessis moves to his right and takes a simple catch. End of an excellent innings from Joe Root but surely he will feel that he missed out on a century. That ends a match-defining partnership. Will this be a match-winning one too? Is a nightwatchman coming?
Full delivery on middle, Root works this past silly mid on. No run.
On off, defended off the front foot by Joe.
Full delivery on middle, Root defends it back to the bowler.
Full ball on middle and leg, Root reverse sweeps it towards deep point for a single.
Down the leg side, Sibley leaves it alone. Quinton de Kock fails to collect it cleanly and the ball rolls to fine leg. A bye taken.
Fuller one on middle, flicked to mid-wicket.
Floated ball down the leg side, Root sweeps it to fine leg for a single.
On middle, defended out off the front foot by Root.
Fullish delivery on middle, Root reverse sweeps it to deep cover and picks up a couple.
Keshav Maharaj has a change of ends. 26-8-75-0 are his numbers so far.
On a length on off, Dominic defends it back to the bowler.
Full delivery outside off, Sibley pushes it past the point fielder and picks up another couple.
On a length on off, Root pushes it to deep cover and takes a single.
Full delivery on off, Root defends it to the off side.
Short of a length ball outside off, Root punches it through point and calls Sibley for a couple.

First signs of hadada on the third day. Sitting behind Philander at mid on. He goes back and asks hadada to go away. It takes off but lands at mid-wicket. No disturbance for anyone though as the play goes on.
Good length ball on off, Root guides it towards gully. He wants the run but as he sees the fielder diving to collect, he decides against it.
Dwaine Pretorius is back into the attack. 10-2-29-0 are his figures so far.
BOUNCER! It is bowled down the leg side, Sibley lets it be.

Short of a length ball on middle, Sibley tucks it to mid-wicket and picks up another single.
Short of a length on middle, Sibley hops and works it to short leg.
BOUNCER! It is bowled around middle and leg, Sibley ducks under it

Floated on middle, Sibley plays it back to the bowler.
Driven through mid off by the batsman. One run added to the total. 250 is now the lead for England.
Short of a length on off, Root cuts but finds the point fielder.
On middle, defended back to the bowler.

FOUR! FIFTY! 46th for him in Tests. Brillaint innings from the skipper. He has played beautifully in this innings. From the first ball, he has looked very comfortable. Maharaj bowls a full delivery on middle, Root sweeps it through the deep square leg region for a boundary. 100-run stand is also up between the two.
Floated on off, Root paddle sweeps it to fine leg for a couple. Rabada comes across from deep square leg and cleans it up.
On middle, defended off the front foot by Sibley.
FOUR! What a shot that one from Sibley! Short of a length ball on middle and leg, Sibley hops and whips it towards the deep mid-wicket region for a boundary.

FOUR BYES! That is poor bowling! Not going to affect Sibley at all. Short of a length ball down the leg side. Sibley leaves it alone and Quinton jumps and tries to collect but fails to do so. It goes into the fence for four byes.

Comes around the wicket and bowls a length ball on middle, Root guides it to gully.

The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Looped up on middle, flicked to the leg side.

Full on middle and leg, worked to mid-wicket.

Drinks! England are moving in smoothly since the Tea break. They are scoring at a brisk pace and have swelled their lead to more than 200.
