On a length on middle, Root solidly defends it out to silly mid on.
Full delivery on middle, Joe defends it back to the bowler.
Good length ball on off, Root defends it out.
FOUR! Cut away beautifully. Short delivery outside off, Sibley rocks on his back foot and cuts it through the point region for the second boundary of the over. The lead  crosses 200.
Maharaj comes around the wicket and bowls a full delivery on off, Sibley takes a stride forward and defends it out.
Fuller one down the leg side, padded away.
Floated on middle, flicked to the leg side for a single.

FOUR! Nicely played! What timing! Flater delivery on middle and leg, Root just pushes it though the mid-wicket region for a boundary. The fielder chases after it but fails to do so. 50-run partnership is also up between the two.
Down the leg side, Root pads it away to the of side.
Full delivery on middel, Sibley pushes it past the silly mid on fielder and towards long on for a single.
Good length ball on off, Dominic defends it to cover.
On a length outside off, Sibley shoulders arms to this one.
Fuller one outside off, Sibley leaves it alone.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Landed on middle, Root works it behind square leg for a single.
FOUR BYES! Another one down the leg side. Sibley leaves it alone. Quinton de Kock fails to collect it and it goes past the diving first slip fielder and into the fence.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Looped up down the leg side, Sibley keeps on padding this one awy.

What has happened there? Luck is going Sibley's way at the moment. Floated ball on middle and leg, Sibley looks to flick but gets a leading edge towards point. Zubayr comes forward to collect but ball spins in front of him and goes past him. Two taken before Hamza can collect it and throw it back.
Down the leg side, Sibley has no problems in padding it away.
Loopy delivery down the leg side, Sibley pads it away.
Root defends this good length ball on off to point.
Fullish on middle, whipped wide of mid on and a single is taken.
Good length ball on off, Sibley defends it to point.
Very full delivery on middle, Dominic gets his bat down in time and whips it to the leg side.
Good length ball on middle, Sibley tucks it to mid-wicket again.
On a length on middle, Sibley works it to mid-wicket.
On middle, it is turned towards mid-wicket for a single.
Padded away again as Maharaj's another attempt of extracting something off the rough fails.
Fuller and on middle, it is driven towards covers for a single.
Around middle, Sibley goes back and punches it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
On the pads again, Sibley pads it away this time.

FOUR BYES! But was it? Flighted ball down the leg side, Root looks to pad it away but the ball misses his attempt. De Kock is blinded by the batsman and he cannot collect the ball and it rolls to the fine leg fence. Now, the umpire signals it four byes. Faf du Plessis is not happy as he tells the umpire brushed the pads and hence it should not be four byes but a dead ball. And replays confirm the same.
Good piece of fielding! Full delivery on middle, Root drives it straight back. Rassie van der Dussen who is standing at silly mid on dives to his left and stops it.
Back of a length ball on off, Root blocks it out onto the pitch.
De Kock comes upto the stumps.
On off, root comes forward and defends it out to the bowler.
Full delivery on off, Root pushes it to point.

Whoa! That hit the crack. Probably first time Pretorius has landed the ball there. It is just behind good length. It pitches and then shoots off. Root awkwardly defends as the ball hits the upper part of his bat.
Fuller ball on off, pushed to mid on.
Flighted on middle, root sweeps it to deep square leg and crosses over for a single.
Loopy on of, pushed to cover.
Flatter delivery down the leg side, Sibley flicks to short leg for a single.
Floated ball on the pads, Sibley pads it away.
Fullish delivery on off, pushed to long off for a single.
Flatter delivery down the leg side, Root looks to play then reverse sweep but then sees it is too wide and then lets it go to the keeper.
On off, pushed towards mid off.
FOUR! No luck this time! It is a proper cricketing shot! Overpitched delivery on middle and leg, Sibley flicks it through mid-wicket and collects a boundary.
EDGY FOUR! Sibley is riding his luck here! Fullish delivery on off, Sibley looks to defend with soft hands but it takes the outside edge and the ball goes through gully and into the fence.
On off, pushed to cover off the front foot.
Full delivery on middle, Sibley pushes it down to mid on.
Full delivery on off, pushed to cover.
Dwaine Pretorius is back on. 2-0-8-0 are his figures so far.
Down the leg side, Root looks to play the sweep it but misses it altogether.
Flighted ball down the leg side, Root looks to play the reverse sweep but gets an inside edge which goes towards first slip.
Quicker one on middle, Root defends it out onto the pitch.
Floated down the leg side, Root pads it away.
Flatter one on off, Sibley pushes it to cover and takes a single.
Floated ball on middle, Root plays the reverse sweep to deep point for a single.
Short ball outside off, Dominic sways away from it.

FIFTY! Maiden fifty for Sibley in Tests! It has been an excellent innings so far. He has got starts in his previous innings but failed to convert it into a big one. He finally has managed to convert one into a half ton. Can he convert this into a maiden ton as well? Good length ball on off, Sibley guides it through gully and picks up a couple.
Back of a length ball outside off, Sibley pushes it to point off the back foot.
On middle, pushed back to the bowler.
BOUNCER! It is bowled around off, Dominic sways away from it.
FOUR! Nicely played from Sibley! Short of a length from Rabada! Sibley stands tall and punches it through the covers for a boundary. Two fielders chase after it but fail to get there. Moves to 48.
The batsman offers no stroke and gets hit on the pad.
Down the leg side, Root pads it away.
FOUR! This is poor bowling from Maharaj! Bowls a full one down the leg side, Root sweeps it past the keeper and into the fence.
Floated ball on the pads, Root looks to defend but hits the pads and rolls to the off side.
Looped up ball down the leg side, Root looks to sweep but misses it altogether.
Just short! Flatter one on off, pitching on the rough. Root plays it with soft hands and guides it to first slip. Luckily, it falls in front of Faf.
Keshav Maharaj will bowl from the other end.
On a length on middle, Dominic works it to mid-wicket.
Good length on off, Sibley defends it to cover.
On middle, defended off the front foot towards mid-wicket.
Fullish ball outside off, Sibley lets the ball go to the keeper.
Back of a length ball on middle, Sibley rocks on his back foot and defends it back to the bowler.
Rabada starts with a short delivery on middle, Root gets the first run of the session by pulling this to deep square leg.

The final session is all set to get underway! Joe Root and Dominic Sibley walk out to the middle. The lead is now 156 and England would want to swell their lead to as much as possible. The South Africans are also making their way out to the ground. Kagiso Rabada will start for the hosts.
... Day 3, Session 3 ...

Not much can be said of the hosts. They bowled tight lines and lengths, especially Maharaj but were not rewarded with a wicket. Nortje was the pick of the bowlers as he kept on bowling short and finally got the reward that South Africa wanted. A wicket. England are still ahead in this game and for the Proteas to make a comeback in this game, they need to pick up quick wickets. Will they be able to do it or will the visitors continue to swell up their lead.

A session that has belonged to England. They have gone about their business smoothly and calmly. They have added just 57 runs but have lost just a one wicket and that was off Denly. Dominic Sibley and Joe Denly started slowly after Lunch and were looking good to go into Tea unscathed but Nortje, at the last moment, bounced out Denly. Since then, Root and Sibley have managed to see out the remaining overs and they go into the break with a lead of 156.
Flatter one on off, Sibley defends it off the back foot. TEA ON DAY 3.
Floated on off, Sibley prods forward and defends it out.
Floated on middle, defended to short leg.
On off, pushed to point and a single is taken.
BEATEN! Not this time says Maharaj. Floated ball down the leg side, Root looks to play the reverse sweep again but misses it and it goes on to hit Quinton de Kock on the chest.
FOUR! Time for some innovation! Maharaj bowls a full delivery on middle, Root goes on his knees and reverse sweeps the ball towards the third man region for a boundary.
Another short one on middle, Root pulls it wide of mid on and crosses over for a single.
Short delivery on middle, Sibley works it to deep square leg and crosses over for a single.
Comes around the wicket and dishes a short ball around middle, Sibley hops and defends it out to short leg.
Back of a length ball on off, Sibley stands tall and blocks it to the off side.
Fullish on middle and leg, Sibley pushes it to mid on.
Short delivery down the leg side, Root pulls it to backward square leg and a single is taken.
Flat one on off, pushed to mid off.
Loopy delivery on the pads spinning away, Sibley looks to defend off the front foot but gets hit on the thigh pad.
Floated on off, Sibley defends it to cover.
On middle, Dominic works it to square leg.
Flatter one on middle, Sibley defends it back to the bowler.
Floated ball on the pads, Sibley looks to pad this one away but gets hit on the elbow area.
Bouncer first up to Root. It is bowled around off, Root sways away from it.
Joe Root is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Finally, we have seen a wicket fall. Brilliant delivery from Nortje. Another start from Denly and he has thrown his wicket away. It has been a trend lately from him. Short delivery on off, Denly looks to pull but it takes the top edge and goes towards fine leg. Pretorius runs forward and tumbles to take an excellent catch. A slow-going but an excellent partnership comes to an end. South Africa would hope that this opens up the floodgates and gives them a chance in this game.
Fullish on off, Denly pushes it to cover.
Short delivery on middle, pulled to mid-wicket.
Very full down the leg side, Denly looks to flick it but misses it. De Kock dives to his left and makes the stop. Seems to have hurt himself in the process.

MISFIELD! Full delivery on middle, Denly pushes it towards mid on where Rabada allows the ball to pass through him and it is rolling towards the fence. By the time Rabada can recover and clean it up, the batters pick up a couple.
Maharaj comes around the wicket and bowls a flat one outside off, Sibley punches it to cover.
Short of a length delivery on middle, Denly pulls it to backward square leg and takes a single.
Down the leg side, Joe once again pads it away.
Tossed up ball on the leg stump line with some extra bounce. Denly looks to pad it away but gets hit on the gloves. No run.
Flatter one down the leg side, Denly pads it away.
Floated on the pads, Denly works it to mid-wicket.
Short of a length outside off, Denly punches it to deep point and takes a single.
Full delivery on off, Joe defends it to mid off.
Comes over the wicket does Nortje and bowls a length ball on off, Denly defends it to point.
BOUNCER! Nortje dishes this one around middle, Denly does well to duck under it.
Back of a length on middle, Sibley tucks it to deep square leg and crosses over for a single.
BOUNCER! It is bowled around middle and leg, Sibley ducks under it.
On off, pushed to mid off.
Looped up ball on middle and leg, Denly works it to mid-wicket.
Tosses this one up on middle, Sibley drives it past the diving Maharaj down to long on for a single.
FOUR! Finally, finally, we see a boundary. Flatter one outside off, Sibley waits for it and punches it through the covers for a boundary.
Flatter one on off, Sibley pushes it to cover.
Looped up ball down the leg side, Denly looks to sweep but it goes off his pads and towards short fine leg. A leg bye taken.
Full ball on middle, pushed down to the man at mid on. End of another over of which only 1 run came.
On off, defended towards the off side by Sibley. The contest has become very stagnant right now with no side coming out with a positive approach.
Back of a length ball on middle, Denly goes back and pulls towards mid-wicket for a single.
Denly rocks back and defends it off the back foot.
Length ball on the body, defended towards the leg side.
Outside off, left alone.
Floated nearer to the off pole now, Sibley prods forward and defends.
Maharaj comes around the wicket and bowls one outside off now. Sibley leaves it alone comfortably.

Another one which is pitched outside leg, Denly sweeps it towards backward square leg for one. It is getting difficult to figure out what the plan is here by the Proteas. They are just conceding runs at the moment without posing any danger.
Pitched outside leg, padded away.
On the pads again, flicked towards square leg for one.
Maharaj comes over the wicket and bowls down the leg side. Denly sweeps but the man at deep backward square leg stops it and the batters take a run.
On the pads, flicked towards the leg side for nothing.
The batsman shoulders arms to let that one through.
Bouncer on off, ducked under.
On the pads of Denly, he looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads. The batters steal a leg bye as the ball rolls towards the leg side.
Length ball on the body, Denly pulls this one towards square leg for a couple.
Nortje starts with a ball outside off, Sibley plays it towards point and takes a run.
Anrich Nortje is back on. 5-1-13-0 are his figures in this innings so far.
Flatter one on off, Denly pushes it to silly point where Pieter Malan makes the stop.
On middle, pushed back to the bowler.
Tossed up ball on the pads, Denly looks to sweep but gets hit on the pads. No harm done.
Floated on middle, Denly blocks it out.
Loopy on middle, Joe works it to mid-wicket.
Floated on middle, Denly pushes it back to the bowler.
Good length ball on middle, pushed down to mid on. Rabada conceding runs unlike Philander who has been super-consistent.
Back of a length ball on middle, pulled to square leg for a single by Denly.
The batsman shoulders arms to let that one through.
Bouncer on middle and off, ducked under by Denly.

Full ball on middle and off, Denly drives it down the ground. Rabada bends down and gets a hand to the ball, trying to deflect it onto the stumps at the non-striker's end but Sibley in the meantime gets back inside the crease.
Rabada starts after the mini-break with a length ball outside off which is left alone by Denly.

DRINKS! England have done really well here after the Lunch break. They are going at a sedate pace but have not lost a wicket. They lead by 127 runs and would be hoping to swell the lead to as much as they can. South Africa, on the other hand, need to break this partnership and then hope to make further inroads to get back in this game.
On middle and leg, Sibley flicks this one towards mid-wicket.
Sibley prods forward and defends this ball.
Bowled outside off by Maharaj, left alone.
Denly has pushed this tossed up delivery towards wide mid off for a single.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Flatter delivery outside off, cut to point for a single.
Back of a length ball on the body, Denly pushes it towards the off side.
Denly goes onto the back foot and has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.

Little bit of indecision here between the batters but in the end no harm done. Good length ball on off, Sibley pushes it towards cover and sets off for a single. Denly is hesitant but obliges very late. The man at cover picks up the ball and has a shy at the striker's end but misses. Replays roll in and show that even if he had hit, Denly was well in.
Good length ball on middle, pushed to the man at mid on.
Outside off, left alone.

FOUR! Creams it! Full ball outside off, Sibley gets down on one knee and drives it in the gap in the cover region for a boundary. 50-run stand comes up with this beautiful stroke. England are effectively 124/1.
On middle and leg, blocked out to the bowler.
Fuller on middle and leg, Denly pushes it to point.
Flighted ball on the pads, Denly looks to sweep it but hits the pads and rolls to square leg.
Looped up down the leg side, Denly prods forward and pads it away again.
Flatter one on middle, Denly defends it to cover.
Floated down the leg side, Denly pads it away.
Another one on middle, Sibley goes on his toes and defends.
Length ball on middle, blocked out off the back foot.
Rabada bowls a full ball on middle, Sibley drives this one straight down the ground but Rabada stops it with his boot and the ball deflects off it towards mid off.
Another one outside off, left alone.
Fullish ball on off, pushed down to the man at mid on.
Length ball outside off, left alone.
Last ball of the over and bowled down the leg side. Padded away by Denly to get through the over.
Outside off this time, Denly blocks it out.
Again outside the leg pole line, Denly pads it away.
Another one which is pitched outside leg, this time Denly goes for a powerful sweep but misses.
Pitched outside leg, Denly pads it away.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Outside off, left alone.
Back of a length ball outside off, Sibley lets the ball go to the keeper.
On a length outside off, Denly punches it through covers and picks up a single.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.

In the air... safe! Well fielded as well. Rabada dishes a good length delivery outside off, Denly drives but does so uppishly. It goes over cover and is racing into the fence. Maharaj hares after it and slides to make an excellent stop. Two taken. The umpire go upstairs to check whether it is a clean save and the replays show that Keshav has done really well.
Good length ball outside off, Denly lets it go to the keeper.
Kagiso Rabada is back on.
Comes around the wicket does Maharaj now and bowls a flighted ball on off, Sibley prods forward and defends it to cover.
Floated on middle, Sibley blocks it to mid-wicket.
Tossed up on the pads, Sibley looks to flick but misses it to get hit on the pads. It lobs off to short leg. Looks like that is the plan.
Down the leg side, padded away by Dominic again.
Floated on middle, blocked out by Sibley.
Maharaj comes over the wicket now, bowls a loopy delivery down the leg side, Sibley pads it away.
Outside off, Denly drives this towards cover but the man there to dive and gather the ball. 6 maidens out of 9 overs for Philander. Unbelievable consistency.
The keeper, Quinton de Kock, has come up to the stumps now.
Philander bowls another one, wicket-to-wicket. Denly defends it onto the pitch.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Full ball on the pads, flicked towards mid-wicket.
Another one which is full in length, Denly pushes it back to Philander who fakes a shy at the striker's end. Trying to ignite a spark.
Full ball on middle and off, driven towards the man at cover.
Another one on off, this time it is pushed to the man at cover-point. 6 runs off the over.
Outside off, played to the man at point.
Tossed up on off, worked to the man at mid on.
This time Denly pushes it towards cover and takes another quick single.
Floated on the off side, Sibley pushes it towards mid off and races through for a single.
FOUR! Full delivery down the leg side, Sibley just helps it fine down the leg side for a boundary.
This time on the hips, Denly works it towards the leg side. 5th maiden out of 8 overs for Philander.
Length ball on off, defended towards the off side.
Fullish outside off, Denly lets it go to the keeper.
On a length on middle, Denly works it to the leg side.
Full delivery on middle, flicked to mid-wicket.
BEATEN! On a length outside off, Denly looks to defend but fails to get any bat on it.
EDGY FOUR! Just wide of Faf at first slip! Lucky, very lucky. Tossed up ball outside off, Sibley looks to drive it but edges it which goes just past the diving Faf at first slip and into the fence.
Floats this one up on off, Sibley looks to defend but it takes the outside edge and goes on the bounce to Faf du Plessis at first slip.
Flatter delivery on middle, worked to the leg side for a single.
Full on middle, Sibley defends it back towards the bowler.
Loopy delivery on off, with some spin on it. Denly defends it towards point.
Up and over! Floated ball on off, Denly strides forward and lifts this over the cover region. The fielder chases after it and cleans it up. The batters take three.
Again Philander bowls one outside off, Sibley makes the leave.
Outside off, left alone by Dominic.
Bowled in the channel outside off, Sibley defends it back towards the bowler.
Length ball on off, played towards point.
Fuller one on middle, driven down to the man at mid on.
Length ball on off, left alone by Sibley.
Another one which is tossed up on off, Denly defends it back to the bowler.
Tossed up on off, Denly pushes this one towards the off side.
FOUR! Maharaj floats one on middle and off, Denly dances down the track and smashes this one over mid off for a boundary. Cries for a catch but no fielder stood a chance.
Floated on off, defended towards the off side by Denly.
Single for Sibley and that brings up the 100-run lead for England. Floated on middle and leg, Sibley works this one towards the man at mid-wicket and takes a quick single to get to the other end.
Little bit of turn again for Maharaj as he floats this one on the off pole line. Sibley works it towards the leg side.
Fuller ball on off, worked down to the man at mid on.
Length ball on off, defended back towards the bowler.
Good length ball on the pads, on middle. Denly flicks it straight to the man at mid-wicket.
Back of a length ball outside off, left alone by Denly.
This time a touch fuller, Denly prods forward and defends it.
Length ball on off, Denly defends it towards the off side off the back foot.
Sibley has pushed that ball towards the off side. Second maiden in a row for Keshav Maharaj.
Tossed up on off, Dominic has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Sibley comes onto the front foot and pushes this ball towards cover. Looks for a single but not on offer.
Outside off, Dominic plays this one towards the man at cover-point.
Floated on off again, Sibley defends with the full face of the bat.
Spin on offer straightaway. Floated on the off pole line, it pitches and turns away from Sibley. Dominic defends solidly though.
Keshav Maharaj will bowl from the other end.

Almost carried that one! Elgar thought he was in the game there. Full ball on middle, Denly works it towards mid-wicket but does so a bit uppishly. The ball is in the air for a bit but falls just short of Elgar.
Length ball on off, defended back towards the bowler.
First run of the session as Sibley works the ball in front of square towards the leg side and takes a single.
Another fullish ball on middle and off, Sibley works it towards the man at short mid-wicket.
Length ball on off, left alone by Dominic.
Philander starts with a full ball on off, Sibley works it to the man at mid on.

We are all set to begin the second session of Day 3. Dominic Sibley and Joe Denly are making their way out to the middle. They have a lead of 98. The Protea players are also making their way out. Vernon Philander will start the proceedings for the hosts. He has three slips in place.
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

So, what does the second session hold in store for us? The track looks pretty lifeless and so do the South African bowlers. Will they be able to come back with more energy in the afternoon session and disrupt the English momentum? Join us after the break to find out!

The day started in perfect fashion for the visiting team as James Anderson dismissed Kagiso Rabada off the first ball of the day. Philander and Nortje stuck around for some time but Anderson struck again to wrap up the innings and give England a 46-run lead. The England openers started in positive fashion, especially Zak Crawley as he punished the bad balls but suffered against some bouncers bowled by Rabada. He eventually lost his battle against the young South African as Kagiso dismissed Zak for 25 runs. Denly then came in and held fort along with Sibley as England go into the Lunch break at 98/1 effectively.

Keshav Maharaj cannot speed through the over and that will be Lunch on Day 3. The England players will be mightily pleased with the proceedings in the morning session as they are comfortably on top in this game.
Looped up ball on off, Denly blocks it to the off side.
Tosses this one up on middle, Joe blocks it out solidly.
Floated ball on off, Denly strides forward and defends it out to silly point.
On off, defended out by Denly.
Loopy delivery on middle, pushed back to Maharaj.
Maharaj starts with a flighted ball on middle, Denly plays it back to the bowler.
Possibly the last over before Lunch and Keshav Maharaj is into the attack. He will try to bowl quickly and buy another over before the break for the Proteas.

Well well! What happened there? On a length on middle, Sibley looks to defend but it goes off the inside edge towards short leg. Sibley moves out of his crease and Pieter Malan at short leg collects the ball but does not throw it back. Sibley has to dive back in his crease.
BOUNCER! Nortje bowls this around middle, Sibley ducks under it.
Full delivery on off, Sibley defends it out.
Short of a length ball on off, Sibley blocks it out to mid on.
BEATEN! Nicely bowled! South Africa have to bowl more on this channel! Back of a length ball outside off, Sibley goes on his back foot to defend but gets squared up and misses it.
Nortje dishes out a full ball on off, Sibley pushes it to mid off.
Fullish delivery on off, Joe blocks it out onto the pitch.
On off, defended solidly off the back foot by Denly.
Good length ball on middle and leg, Denly works it to mid-wicket.
Fullish delivery on off, Joe defends it off the front foot back to the bowler.
Denly defends this length ball on middle to the leg side.

FOUR! Beautiful shot from Denly. Low full toss on middle, Denly whips it through mid-wicket and the ball goes into the fence. The Proteas are losing their lines and lengths out in the middle. 50 up for the visitors.
FOUR! This is poor, poor bowling from Nortje. Short of a length delivery on the pads, Sibley works it to the fine leg region for a boundary. The lead now moves to 94.
Back of a length on off, Denly defends it to cover and takes a quick single.
Short of a length ball outside off, Denly sways away from it.
Full on middle, Denly pushes it to mid on.
OHH! Good length ball on middle, nipping in, Joe looks to flick it but gets hit on the thigh pad.
Fuller one on off, Denly pushes it back to Nortje.
Good length ball on middle, Sibley solidly blocks it out.
Outside off, left alone.
FOUR! That's not the place to bowl to Sibley. He is very strong there. Full delivery on middle, Sibley whips it through mid-wicket and the ball races into the fence.
Good length delivery on middle, Sibley defends it out.

An appeal for LBW but it is turned down. On a length on middle, Sibley looks to flick but gets hit on the elbow and the ball goes onto the pads before rolling to the leg side. Pretorius appeals but nothing from the umpire. The Proteas think of a review but decide against it.
Pretorius starts with a length ball outside off, Sibley shoulders arms to it.
Dwaine Pretorius is into the attack for the first time in this innings.
On the hips of Denly, he works the ball towards the man at square leg.
This time pushes the length ahead a bit does Nortje. Denly drives the ball towards mid on.
Length ball on middle and off, Denly hops and works this one towards the leg side.
This time a length ball on the off pole line, the batter blocks it out.
Length ball on off, left alone by Denly.
Good length ball on the off pole line, worked towards the mid-wicket region for a single.

FOUR! That is a beautiful way to get off the mark. Rabada dishes out a full delivery on off, Denly gets into position and creams the drive through mid off for a boundary. Nortje runs after it but fails to get there in the end.
Fullish delivery on off, Denly prods forward and defends it out.
Back of a length delivery on middle, Sibley works it to square leg and crosses over for a single. The fielder has a shy at the keeper's end but misses. Denly was in though.
Full delivery outside off, Sibley shoulders arms to it.
Good length ball on off, Dominic defends it out to cover.
FOUR! Poor delivery from Rabada! Full delivery on the pads, Sibley will not miss out on those. He just flicks it towards the deep square leg region for a boundary.
On off, defended back to the bowler.
Back of a length ball on off, Denly hops and defends it out.
Length ball on middle, Denly looks to work it to the leg side but gets hit on the thigh pad.
Snorker of a delivery from Nortje! Short of a length ball on middle, Sibley looks to defend but gets hit on the gloves and the ball lobs towards square leg. A single taken.
Fullish delivery on middle, Sibley works it to mid-wicket.
Joe Denly is the new man in.
Good length ball on off, Sibley camps back and blocks it out to the leg side.
Good length delivery on off, Denly defends it to mid on.

OUT! CAUGHT! Excellent catch from Quinton de Kock and Rabada gets his reward for persistent bowling. Brilliant stuff! Fullish delivery outside off, Crawley looks to go for the cover drive without moving his feet. The bat turns a bit in his hand and the ball goes off the outside edge between first slip and the keeper. De Kock dives to his right and pouches it with both his hands in front of Rassie van der Dussen who was moving to his left. Rabada is ecstatic. Can they get another wicket before Lunch? Joe Denly walks out to bat at number 3, replacing the free-flowing Zak Crawley.
Good length ball on middle, Sibley works it to the leg side for a single.
Fullish outside off, Sibley once again makes a leave to this one.
Full delivery outside off, Dominic lets the ball go to the keeper.
Good length ball outside off, Sibley shoulders arms to this one.

Drinks! An excellent hour of play for England. They bowled out South Africa first and then have survived the first hour unscathed. Sibley is looking good out there while Crawley, after looking uncomfortable at the start against Rabada has started to get into the groove. The English openers now would be looking to build onto their lead. South Africa desperately need wickets to get back in this game.
The batsman has driven it towards mid off.
BEATEN! Short of a length outside off, Zak looks to punch it off the back foot but fails to make any connection with it.

Excellent fielding! Short of a length ball on middle, Crawley pulls it away handsomely towards deep mid-wicket but Pretorius comes across from deep square leg and slides to collect it with just a single hand. Two taken.
Back of a length delivery on off, Crawley rocks back and defends it out.
Full delivery outside off, Zak leaves it alone.

EDGY FOUR! Anrich Nortje comes into the attack and induces an edge straightaway. Starts with a length ball around off, Crawley looks to drive but gets a thick outside edge which flies through the empty gully region and into the third man fence.
First change! Anrich Nortje is into the attack.
On off, Sibley defends it off the back foot to point.
Back of a length on middle, Sibley works it to square leg for nothing.
Good length on middle and leg, Sibley tucks it to mid-wicket.
Fullish outside off, Sibley lets it go to the keeper.
BEATEN! Brilliant from Rabada! Back of a length ball in the channel of uncertainty. Sibley looks to defend off the back foot but it whizzes past the bat and into the mitts of the keeper.
Length ball outside off, Sibley leaves it alone.

FOUR! Good stuff from Crawley. He hasn't had it easy out there but this will give him some confidence. Philander dishes out a full delivery on middle, Zak whips it to the deep mid-wicket region for a boundary.
Good length ball outside off, Crawley shoulders arms to this one.
Fullish delivery outside off, nipping in a little. Zak lets it through to the keeper.
Good length ball on middle, Crawley flicks it to mid-wicket.
Good length ball on the fourth stump line, Zak does not fiddle with it and leaves it alone.
Full delivery outside off, Crawley leaves this ball alone.
Length ball on middle, Sibley solidly pushes it back to mid on.
Back of a length ball on off, Sibley stands tall and blocks it out to point.
On middle, flicked to deep square leg for a single.
FOUR! Very full delivery down the leg side, Crawley just helps it on its way to the fine leg region for a boundary.
Short of a length ball on middle, Crawley hops and defends it to short leg.
Another nasty one! Back of a length ball on middle, Zak attempts to flick this one but it goes on to hit the thigh pad. Rabada has been all over Crawley so far in this opening session.
Well fielded! Fuller one outside off, Sibley drives this beautifully towards mid off. Maharaj comes across and slides to make an excellent stop.

Appeal by South Africa but turned down! Height maybe? Good length ball around off, swinging in. Sibley shoulders arms but gets hit on the thigh pad. Philander appeals but the umpire Kumar Dharmasena shakes his head, signalling height as the issue. South Africa did not even consider going for the review.
Fuller one outside off, this one is coming in. Sibley shoulders arms to this one.
Full delivery on off, moving away. Sibley defends it to point.
Good length on off, Dominic this time solidly blocks it out to cover.
Good length ball on off nipping away. Sibley attempts to defend it but takes the outside edge and goes towards gully.
Length ball on off, Crawley defends it out.

BOUNCER! It is bowled around middle and leg, Crawley looks to duck under but gets hit on the shoulder. Rabada gives a look after that delivery to Zak. Rabada will be looking to pepper Crawley with some more short stuff as Zak is clearly struggling against the bouncers.
Good length ball on off, Crawley defends it to the off side.
Fullish delivery outside off, Crawley shoulders arms to this one.
There is a slight halt in play as Crawley is checking his helmet after getting hit on the last ball from Rabada.
Nasty!!! Short of a length ball on off, Crawley looks to pull the ball but it hits the edge of the bat and goes onto hit the grill of the helmet.
Good length delivery on off, keeping a little low. Crawley gets his bat down in time and defends it to the leg side.
On a length outside off, Sibley lets it go to the keeper.
Sibley is away! Good length ball on middle, Sibley works it to backward square leg and picks up a couple.
Outside off, left alone by Sibley.
Good length delivery on off, Sibley defends it to point.
On a length outside off, Dominic does not fiddle with it and shoulders arms to it.
Full delivery on off, Sibley defends it back to the bowler.
On middle and leg, worked to mid-wicket.
Back of a length ball outside off, Crawley shoulders arms to it.
Full delivery nipping in a little, Crawley makes a good leave to this one.
Length ball on middle, Crawley works it through square leg and takes a couple before the fielder can clean it up.
On a length on off, Crawley solidly defends it back to the bowler.

Good length ball on off, Sibley pushes it to point off the front foot.
Sibley defends this good length ball on middle and leg towards the man mid-wicket.

Vernon Philander will bowl from the other end.

Rabada ends the over by bowling a length ball on middle, Crawley looks to defend but the ball goes off the inside edge and rolls towards fine leg. Good start to the innings for England as 8 runs come off the over.
FOUR! Crawley has come out as a confident man here. This time it is a full ball on off by Rabada, Crawley gets on the front foot and just drives it through mid off for a boundary.
On off again, driven to the man at mid off.
Again Rabada bowls one outside off, Crawley leaves it alone.
FOUR! England are underway and in style! Full ball on the pads, Crawley flicks this one off his pads and the ball races away to the mid-wicket fence.
Rabada starts with a length ball outside off, it is left alone by Zak Crawley.

Woah, That brings us to the end of a Test match which will be remembered for a long time. The pendulum swung from England to South Africa a lot of times but it is England who in the end run away with the points. 30 to be precise in the ICC World Test championship. That's not all from this exciting series though. The caravan now moves to Port Elizabeth for the Third Test match. It will begin on 16th of January at 1000 Local (0800 GMT). Until then, ciao!

BEN STOKES IS NAMED MAN OF THE MATCH. He tries to drag Sibley with him as he wants to share the award with him but he pulls himself away from Stokes. Ben starts by saying that he came in to bowl in a do-or-die situation. Tells that Sibley deserves a lot of credit too. On his own performance, Stokes says that credit should be given to the whole group for the way they played the in entire game. On the catch by Crawley, Stokes says that he felt that it would go over but he did well to latch onto it. Tells that it is a game to remember for England and feels that South Africa too will remember this for a long time. Feels games like these are reasons why five day Tests should always be around.

England skipper, Joe Root, starts by saying that it was a great game of cricket. Tells that they believed every minute of the game that they could win the game and thanks the crowd for coming in large numbers. Tells that South Africa made things difficult for them but their 12th man, the crowd, was brilliant. On the bounce back after the defeat, Root feels that they had individual players standing up for him during tough situations. Feels that Stokes' impact once again helped them in this game. On the wicket of van der Dussen, Root says the credit goes to Stuart Broad for that wicket. On Ben Stokes' performance, Root says that he is one of those players who gives his 100 percent for the side. Adds that he is a world-class player and deserves every compliment that comes his way.

South Africa skipper, Faf du Plessis, says that they fought and fought throughout the game and it is unfortunate that there has to be a winner. Credits England for coming at them relentlessly. Tells that with the series level now, the next game is going to be an exciting one. Praises Malan's effort and feels that the transition phase is always worrying but Malan's effort helps the team in such a phase. Tells that he does not mind losing here as they fought really hard in this game. On the conditions, du Plessis said that conditions change everywhere. Tells that two tough and very good games have been played. Says that they will regroup and try to do better in the next game.

Quinton de Kock is now down for a chat with Shaun Pollock. De Kock starts by saying that the boys fought hard but credits the English bowlers for a superb performance. Tells that they tried to take the game as deep as they could. On his wicket, he says that it felt really bad. Tells that he will try to stay away from the game for a couple of days and then regroup for the next game. On Philander's last game at Newlands, and eventually his retirement post the series, de Kock says that he is a special player and that they will miss him in the dressing room. The players are now down again for the presentation.

Zak Crawley is down for a quick chat with Pommie Mbangwa. He starts by saying that it was an exceptional game. On Stokes' performance, says that he was very good. On the catch of Nortje, Crawley says that it came really quickly at him and the ball popped up. Feels he was lucky there as it went up and he managed to pouch it with his other hand. Dominic Sibley comes to talk to Mbangwa now. He says that it's an amazing win. On things not going their way, Sibley says that before this session, things looked really flat but they did not give up. Says that Stokes is an amazing player and he gets things done for the side.

Stuart Broad is down for a chat with Shaun Pollock. He starts by saying that this win is a special one and mentions that the crowd has been exceptional in this game. Reckons South Africa played brilliantly too but felt that they knew that they needed one magic moment and things will change. On the wicket of Rassie van der Dussen, Broad says that he did not plan that ball, adds that he actually sprayed down the leg side unintentionally and luckily it got him the big wicket. Tells that the wicket got slow as the final day approached and tells that Stokes' innings yesterday gave them a lot of time to bowl them out.

So, a summary of this Test match overall. South Africa put in a good performance in the first innings with the ball as they restricted England to only 269 with Nortje, Rabada and Philander being the pick of the bowlers. England responded even better with Anderson and Broad being the pick of the bowlers. Anderson picked up a 5-fer as they got a lead of 46. Dominic Sibley, then in the second bout, registered his maiden Test ton and contributions from Big Ben and others gave a target of 438 to the Proteas which ultimately proved to be enough as the English Lions won the game by 189 runs.

The hosts, on the other hand, started well. They blocked whatever was thrown at them but maybe an extremely defensive approach hurt them. Pieter Malan was the star for them with a brilliant 84 on his debut in the second innings. He along with Rassie van der Dussen, who played 140 balls for his 17 looked the most comfortable batters out there. The Proteas skipper would be disappointed with himself as he threw his wicket away. Just when de Kock and van der Dussen were making things look easy, the former played a poor shot and he too got out. Rassie van der Dussen soon followed with a strangle down the leg side and then it all went downhill. The last four wickets fell in quick succession and that gave the visitors a hard-fought victory.

The second innings did not start well for the visitors. Elgar and Malan stood tall and gave a good start to the South Africans. Even Elgar's wicket did not stop the Proteas. Faf du Plessis and Quinton de Kock gave a fight but once the latter fell, England pounced upon that opportunity and finished things off quickly for the visitors. Despite Anderson being injured almost throughout the final session, the other bowlers bowled brilliantly especially Stokes in the end. He was the one with the three final wickets. Anderson picked up two wickets and all the other bowlers also chipped in with wickets. Overall, it was a very good performance from the visitors in the second innings.

Wow! What a Test match we have witnessed! A match surely to remember for a long time. Stokes you beauty! Brilliant! England deserve every bit of it. At Tea, it looked like Quinton de Kock and Rassie van der Dussen would bat out the session and settle for the draw but England persisted and it paid off in the end.  It all started with the wickets of Quinton de Kock and Rassie van der Dussen who threw them away. Philander and Pretorius held fort for some time but then, it was the Ben Stokes show as he took two wickets off two balls. Philander was the last man to fall and that gave England the all-important victory, their first in this decade.

OUT! CAUGHT! Heartbreak for Vernon Philander and South Africa after coming so close. England have come out on top after what has been a riveting game. Stokes is the hero as he has harassed and dislodged three stubborn tailenders. Stokes bowls a length ball just outside off, Philander looks to fend at it and the ball goes off the splice of the bat and into the hands of Ollie Pope at gully who takes the catch. What a great advert this has been for Test cricket! ENGLAND WIN THE MATCH BY 189 RUNS!!!
Another length ball outside off, left alone by Philander.
In the channel outside off, Philander makes a leave now. The crowds getting into the act now as almost every ball is getting cheered.
Good length ball on off, defended.
Almost another one! Fires this just outside off, Rabada pokes at it but misses.
Fires this one outside off, Rabada strokes it through point. No one in the deep so an easy couple for Rabada. They don't matter though.
Floated one on middle, Rabada keeps it out.
Full again and on middle, pushed to covers.
Full again, Rabada pushes it back to the bowler. A bit uppish but does not carry.
Floats a very full ball on middle, Rabada easily blocks it out.
Over negotiated but the strike with Rabada now. Very full ball on middle and off, Philander blocks it out.
Back of a length ball outside off, Philander makes an easy leave.
A length ball just outside off, Philander stays tall and defends.
A very full ball on middle and leg, Rabada gets his bat down and turns the ball towards mid-wicket so that he can give the strike to the local boy Philander.
Bouncer on middle and off, Rabada ducks under it.
Good length ball on middle and leg, Rabada looks to defend but misses to get hit on the thigh pad.

FOUR! Runs do not matter at this stage as the ball has crossed the boundary line and the strike will be with Rabada for the next over. Full ball on off, Philander softly drives but the ball trudges into the fence.
Philander defends it from within the crease. Will be looking to retain strike for the next over.
Again outside off, Philander defends towards cover.
Bess goes a touch too straight and lands the ball on middle. Worked towards the leg side.
Now tossed up closer to the off pole, Vernon prods forward and blocks.
Floated outside off, defended towards the off side by Philander.
Shortish ball outside off, Rabada rides the bounce and taps it towards point.
No hat-trick! An yorker attempt gone wrong and Stokes ends up dishing out a full toss. Rabada pushes it towards mid on.
Kagiso Rabada is the last man in. He will face the hat-trick ball. Remember, he is on a king pair.

OUT! Caught! Oh dear! What a blinder from Crawley. Stokes you champion. Crawley you little beauty. A good length ball angled away from wide of the crease. It pitches and shapes a hint away as Nortje looks to defend at it with hard hands. The ball takes the thick outside edge and goes to Crawley at third slip. It is traveling at him. He puts his right hand out to grab it but the ball does not stick and pops up. He keeps his eyes on the ball and sees it coming down. He then puts his left hand up and takes it easily. England celebrate. Just one wicket away from leveling the series. Stokes on a hat-trick. Absolute scenes here in Cape Town.
Anrich Nortje walks in. An Everest in front of him. 75 minimum balls to survive.

OUT! CAUGHT! Another one goes down and England are jubilant! Everyone has come up to Stokes and are giving him a hug and why not! It was a low, low catch and Root has done extremely well to take it. Maybe this is the price that the South Africans have to pay for not rotating the strike when a single is on offer. Length ball in the corridor of uncertainty, Pretorius looks to defend but the ball goes off the outside edge low to the right of first slip where Root takes a very good low catch.
This time on the off pole line, Pretorius defends it towards the off side.
Starts the over with a length ball on the hips, Dwaine defends it towards the leg side.

Fuller and outside off, Philander pushes it to deep point and does not take a single. Why would he do that? Probably planning to play out the spinner himself and let Pretorius face Stokes. Interesting!
Flighted fuller ball around off, pushed past the silly point fielder.
Full and on off, Philander comes forward and keeps it out.
Fuller again and outside off, pushed to covers.
Fuller and on off, it is defended.
Quicker one around off, Philander keeps it out.
Rise up England fans, cheer us on... that is the word from skipper Joe Root!!! He is trying to extract each and every ounce of energy that he can get from every source possible.
This time Pretorius keeps it out.
Beaten again! Another ball in the channel outside off, Pretorius once again looks to defend but misses out again.
That kept low! How did Pretorius manage to keep it out. A fullish length ball, hitting one of the cracks and keeping really low. Pretorius gets his bat down in time to block it out.
Another ripper! Brilliant from Stokes. Another length ball, this is closer to the off pole. This time Pretorius has to play. He looks to defend but gets beaten again.
Almost! Almost! Stokes looks for the heavens as he cannot believe it. A good length ball outside off, seaming away. Pretorius can leave it alone easily but he pokes to get beaten.
Back of a length ball down the leg side. Pretorius lets its be.

DRINKS! 15 more overs to go, and 3 wickets in hand. The match stays at a tantalising stage with so many factors in play. James Anderson is struggling badly with an injury, Stuart Broad already has 2 official warnings for running onto the danger area and Ben Stokes has run himself into the ground. Kumar Dharmasena signals the final hour is underway and Stokes will get us started for it. Nervous times for both teams!
OHH! Floated on off, Vernon looks to defend but it takes the inside half of the bat and goes wide of the short leg fielder.
FOUR! Bang! Flighted on off, Philander leans forward and drives it through covers for a boundary.

Almost! Stokes getting closer! Length ball in the corridor of uncertainty outside off, Pretorius looks to drive but the ball goes past the outside edge. Misses it by a whisker. Another over negotiated by this pair.

Floated outside off, Philander tries to force it towards cover but misses.
Fullish and on off, it is blocked.
Fuller and on off, pushed.
Second official warning for Stuart Broad as he runs on the danger area on the pitch. If he does so again, Broad will be taken off.
Back of a length ball down the leg side. Pretorius lets it be.
Good length ball hits the crack and goes miles away as Pretorius lets it be.
Full and on middle this time, Pretorius gets solid behind the line of the delivery.
Fullish and on off, Pretorius defends it.
Quicker one outside off, Philander lets it be.

Flatter one around off, pushed to mid off again.

Quicker one around off and middle, Philander defends it off the front foot.
Fuller and on middle, it is defended by Philander.

OUT! CAUGHT! Disaster strikes as the last recognised batter and the pillar for the Proteas in this innings, Rassie van der Dussen departs! It was a clear trap and Rassie has completely fallen for it. A leg gully was in place and the ball has gone straight to him. Broad sprays this one down the leg side, van der Dussen gets tempted and looks to flick. He does so but the ball goes very fine for his liking. Rassie turns and watches Anderson take an easy catch. Van der Dussen is in distraught and so are his teammates in the pavilion. He walks back after a gritty and fantastic knock, facing 140 balls. Has he done enough to help his team drag this match to a draw? Only the remaining batters can complete the story now.
Again Broad sprays one outside off, not troubling van der Dussen.
This time Broad attacks the stumps but van der Dussen does well to prod forward and defend.
Outside off, left alone. Too easy for van der Dussen.
Down the leg side, van der Dussen has no need to go after it.

Outside off, played towards point.
Philander goes back in his crease and now defends it towards the short leg fielder.

Tossed up on middle, worked towards the leg side.
Floated on off, Philander prods forward and defends.

Broad dishes one outside off, tempting van der Dussen to drive but he is not interested as he makes another leave to the keeper.

Fullish on middle, pushed to mid-wicket.
Broad goes full on middle, Rassie defends it out to the leg side.
On a length outside off, van der Dussen shoulders arms to it.
Length ball on off, Rassie defends it off the back foot to cover.
Flatter delivery on middle, Vernon stands tall and defends it out.
Low full toss on middle, worked to mid on.
On middle, pushed back to the bowler.

Looped up ball on off, defended to silly point off the front foot.
Loopy delivery on middle, Philander defends it out to the bowler.
Back of a length ball outside off, van der Dussen shoulders arms to it.
Length ball on off, Rassie stands tall and defends it out to cover.
Good length ball outside off, Rassie shoulders arms to this one.
Length ball on middle, Rassie defends it to the leg side.
Outside off, left alone by Rassie van der Dussen.
Full delivery on off, pushed to cover.

NOT OUT! That's off the pad first and then maybe the elbow. England lose both their reviews and honestly, this is a bad call from Root. Floated outside off by Denly, Philander does not attempt to play a shot and leaves. The ball hits his pad as it is turning away from him. It loops towards the fielder at silly point who takes it. The England players put in an appeal but the umpire has turned it down. They mull over a review and take it in the end. Replays roll in and show that it has hit Philander's pad first. There is no chance of LBW as the ball has pitched outside off and is spinning further away. Ball Tracker does not even come in and the game resumes as Philander survives.

Is that another one? Will Philander also walk back? The umpire disagrees but England think that Philander has got either bat or glove on that one as Root opts for the review. It is an appeal for a catch at silly point. Replays roll in and show that the ball has hit the pad first and then maybe hits the elbow. Philander made the leave but the ball is in no way hitting the wickets as well. Review wasted!
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Vernon Philander walks out to bat for the last time on his home ground. Can he grind it out along with Rassie and save his nation from the jaws of defeat?

OUT! Caught! Oh dear, de Kock, what have you done? Pulled it straight to the short mid-wicket fielder. He cannot believe it. A long hop from Denly on middle, de Kock looks to hammer it over mid-wicket but ends up slamming it straight to Crawley at short mid-wicket. He  does not make any mistake there and England have got the breakthrough they were after. 4 wickets away now. De Kock is distraught as he walks off.
Another one pitched outside off and turning in. It is defended.

Fuller and outside off, forced towards cover.
Joe Denly to bowl now. First time in this session. 16-2-42-1 are his figures so far.
Good length ball around off, van der Dussen keeps it out.

Beaten! Nicely bowled! Fuller and outside off, van der Dussen this time is drawn into the shot as he comes forward and looks to drive. The ball moves away just a hint to go past the bat.
Finally on the stumps line on a good length, van der Dussen blocks it off the front foot.

Broad too starts with a good length ball outside off, van der Dussen makes a leave.

FOUR! Fifty for de Kock. What a fighting innings from him. Probably slowest of his career but that's what is need of the hour. Very full ball outside off, de Kock creams it through covers and it races to the fence. He is not done yet though and would look to bat it out.
Good length ball around off, blocked.
Landed on a good length around off, blocked.
Fullish on off, de Kock comes forward and defends it out.
Fuller and on off, worked towards the leg side.

Outside off, left alone.

And Curran bowls a good length ball outside off, hoping for an edge which can fly towards that fielder. That does not happen and de Kock stands tall and taps it to the third man fence.
Shortish around off, blocked.
On middle, it is defended.
FOUR! Nicely guided! Curran rolled his fingers on this one and bowled it outside off, de Kock waits and then runs it down to third man. No protection there and the ball races to the fence.

Outside off, another leave from van der Dussen.
Outside off on a good length again, van der Dussen makes another leave.

We are back for the final session of the game. England need 5 wickets to win while the hosts need to survive 30 odd overs to draw this Test and remain 1-0 up. Quinton de Kock and Rassie van der Dussen make their way out to the middle. The England players follow them out to the middle. James Anderson will start the proceedings for the visitors. He has figures of 16-7-23-2.
... Day 5, Session 3 ...

31 overs are left in the day. 16 of those, without a wicket, could force Joe Root into shaking hands. Can South Africa survive? England look a bit tired but we all know what boost a wicket can make. They still have a very good chance of leveling the series. Let's see how things pan out in the final session. Join us back at 3.30 pm local (1330 GMT) for the final session. Expecting a cracker!

England, on the other hand, would've hoped that the wicket of the debutant will give them an opening but that's not how things panned out for them. They have not bowled badly, but they have also not been able to break this stubborn stand between Rassie and Quinton. Here and there, we have witnessed some grubbers while a couple of balls have shot up as well. So it could well be a matter of a wicket before a collapse ensues.

The afternoon session of Day 5 is all set to get underway!!! Pieter Malan and Rassie van der Dussen are making their out to the middle. The England players also follow them out to the field. Stuart Broad will bowl after the break.
... Day 5, Session 2 ...

So England need 6 wickets, South Africa need to bat out two sessions to save this Test. When we started the day, all three results looked possible but after the first session, South Africa's win looks unlikely. Can England find a way to get a couple of wickets and get back on the ascendancy in this game or will the Proteas continue to annoy the English Lions? Join us after the break to find out.

South Africa will be happy with their efforts in this session. They lost Maharaj early but Faf du Plessis and Pieter Malan made the visitors toil hard. The skipper though after setting his eyes in, got out playing a shot which one would feel was absolutely not needed. The good news for the hosts is that debutant Malan is still out there and has taken international Test cricket to fish like water. He is continuing his marathon knock and having faced 271 balls, he now finds himself just 17 short of getting his maiden Test ton on debut. He is joined by another inexperienced international Test batter, Rassie van der Dussen. The pair have managed to bat out till Lunch and would look to continue their good work after the break. Pieter Malan, on his first ever Test already holds the key for the hosts in this game.

An even session of this exciting final day here in Newlands. The visitors managed to get rid of the nightwatchman earlier and then they had to work hard to get the Protea skipper but they will be happy with their efforts. Anderson was brilliant with the old ball at the start and rightfully got a wicket. Broad had a short spell but hardly troubled in it. Stokes bowled his heart out but was unable to reap the reward. Dominic Bess was the other bowler who got the dangerous Faf du Plessis. The visitors though would have liked one more. The visitors know that they will be made to work hard as Pieter Malan is still out there and Rassie van der Dussen has been doing his job to negotiate the new ball which is now just three overs old.

Buttler dives to his right and takes a good catch. Sam is interested and appeals but the umpire is unmoved. Now then, the England players think of a review but decide against it. Right decision in the end as the Ultra Edge shows that there there was no bat and it had gone off the thigh pad. With that, it is LUNCH ON DAY 5.

We are all set to begin Day 5! Pieter Malan and Keshav Maharaj are making their way out to the middle. The England players follow them out to the ground. James Anderson will begin the proceedings for the visitors.

Welcome to the coverage of Day 5 of the second Test between South Africa and England. The game is evenly poised heading into the final day and all three results are possible. The visitors might feel they are slightly ahead coming into the final day but the hosts too will fancy themselves. Will England head to Port Elizabeth with the series level or will South Africa manage to maintain their lead?
... Day 5, Session 1 ...

So, England need 8 wickets to level the series. South Africa need 312 runs more to take an unassailable 2-0 lead in this 4-match series. The hosts' other option to stay 1-0 up in the series is to bat out the 3 sessions on Day 5. England are on top but South Africa are not out of this contest. What do we have in store on the final day of this fascinating Test? Join us on Tuesday, 7th January 2020 for the 5th and final day of this Test to  find out which way the pendulum swings. The play will begin at 1030 local (0830 GMT). Join us then, till then cheers!

England would be the happier of the sides with their efforts. Ben Stokes' quick-fire 72 along with Buttler's cameo around Dominic Sibley's maiden Test ton ensured the visitors could declare with a huge lead of 437. The tourists did not have as good an outing with the ball like they did with the bat. They struggled initially to get through the openers' defense. But part-timer, Joe Denly was the unlikely source who got them their first breakthrough. The ball started to do something towards the latter stages of the day. And when the ball talks, James Anderson roars, and he once again roared providing his team a prized scalp of Zubayr Hamza.

A very good day of Test cricket for England. But South Africa would also be happy with their efforts, especially with the bat.  England were first dominant with the bat and ended up declaring with a massive lead of 437! Needing 438 to win, South Africa needed their openers to lay in a solid platform and build a big stand. The pair of Elgar and Malan did just that. The duo took their sweet time and calmly stitched a 71-run opening stand. Elgar failed to capatalize on his start, Hamza then joined Pieter out in the middle and continued from where Elgar left off. But just like Dean Elgar, Zubayr Hamza too fought hard but failed to stick around. Nightwatchman, Keshav Maharaj who had a torrid time with the ball then joined the well-set Malan and ensured that there were no further damage done.

Replay rolls in and Ultra Edge shows that there is a feather on it as it shows a small spike as the ball goes past the bat. Elgar is shocked as he trudges back to the pavilion. Can't blame Elgar for this as it was the slightest of feather which he might not have felt. He was looking very good out in the middle but needed to continue for his side. We are all set to begin the final session of Day 4.  Dean Elgar and Pieter Malan are making their way to the field.  England players follow them out to the middle after being in a huddle. Joe Denly will start the proceedings after the break for the visitors. There is a silly point in place for him.
... Day 4, Session 3 ...

Very good session for the hosts. They have managed to bat this passage of play without losing a wicket. After England declared  with a massive lead of 437, South Africa would have hoped for a steady, resilient fight from their openers. Dean Elgar and Pieter Malan have done just that. They have not scored at a very high run rate but the pair have taken their time and are fighting it out in the middle. The hosts will hope that the pair continues their good work after the break and bat the majority of the final session as well. England, on the other hand, have a good chunk of runs to play with but they cannot take it lightly and will need to strike a couple of wickets before the end of day's play. Part-timer Denly has used the rough and Root will hope Bess too can exploit that. Can the Proteas bat the day out without losing a wicket or will England strike in the final session of the day? Join us after the break to find out.

What happened there? England do not go for the review in the end. It was very close! Excellent umpiring from Paul Reiffel. Length ball around off, nipping into the batsman. Malan looks to defend off the front foot, there are two noises as the ball goes to the right of the keeper. Buttler behind the stumps dives on that side and takes it just above the ground. Buttler along with the other English players put in a huge appeal but the umpire shakes his head. Stokes, Buttler, Sibley and Root all gather and have a brief chat but  Anderson is not interested at all. He starts going back for his run up. In the end, they opt against the review. Probably the last review made them not go for it for this one. Very good decision in the end not to go for the review and Anderson not being excited is justified as Ultra Edge rolls in later on and it shows that the ball had kissed the front pad and not the bat before clipping the back leg and going to the keeper. Hawk Eye then comes in and it shows that the impact was outside off and the wicket was missing too. It would have been disastrous as the tourists would have lost both their reviews so early in this innings.

NOT OUT! England lose their review! But what a decision from Kumar Dharmasena. This is top, top umpiring from the Sri Lankan. Brilliant ball from Broad. It is full and just around off. It jags back in viciously. Malan looks to defend but the ball hits the pad. The English players put in a huge appeal but the umpire turns it down. The English core of Broad, Stokes, Buttler and Root have a word and in the dying moments Root takes it upstairs. Replay rolls in and first it shows Broad is clean as his front foot is inside the crease. Time for Ultra Edge and ... it shows a spike as the ball goes past the bat. There is a feather of an inside edge. It looked plumb but tell you what, the umpire has produced a world class decision. Can't blame Root for taking it upstairs. England lose one of their two reviews. Malan survives, so South Africa are spared off a disastrous start.
